{"title_page": "Stellera", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n|image = Stellera chamaejasme 2.jpg\n|display_parents = 2\n|genus = Stellera\n|parent_authority = L.<ref name=IPNI_39323-1/> \n|species = chamaejasme\n|authority = L.<ref name=TPL_Stellera/>\n}}\n\n'''''Stellera''''' is a [[genus]] of [[flowering plant]] in the family [[Thymelaeaceae]], with a single species '''''Stellera chamaejasme''''',<ref name=TPL_Stellera/> found in mountainous regions of [[Central Asia]], [[China]], [[Siberia]] and [[South Asia]]. ''S.&nbsp;chamaejasme'' is a herbaceous [[perennial]] plant with heads of white, pink or yellow flowers, grown as an ornamental plant in [[rock garden]]s and [[alpine house]]s, but considered a [[weed]] playing a r\u00f4le in the [[desertification]] of grasslands in parts of its native range. Like many others of its family, it is a [[poisonous plant]] with medicinal and other useful properties.\n\n==Scientific Name==\n\n[[File:Pink jasmine bush.jpg|thumb|''[[Jasminum polyanthum]]'' in bloom, showing wine-red exteriors of corollas reminiscent of those of ''Stellera'' (re. species name ''chamaejasme'' i.e. \"ground jasmine\").]]\nThe [[Monotypic taxon|monotypic genus]] ''Stellera'' (not to be confused with the entirely unrelated ''[[Stellaria]]'') commemorates [[Georg Wilhelm Steller]] (St\u00f6ller), while the specific epithet ''chamaejasme'' is a rendering into botanical Latin orthography of the Greek \u03c7\u03b1\u03bc\u03b1\u03af ''khamai'' \"(down) on the ground\" and \u03b9\u03b1\u03c3\u03bc\u03b5 ''iasme'' \"[[jasmine]]\". The name in its entirety thus means \"Steller's plant that resembles a kind of jasmine (that creeps) on the ground\". The name of the species is doubly apt, as not only is the flower of ''Stellera chamaejasme'' fragrant like that of jasmine, but it also has a wine-red exterior, like that of certain species of jasmine e.g. Common jasmine ''[[Jasminum officinale]]'' and the Chinese species ''[[Jasminum polyanthum]]''. Unlike jasmine, however, ''Stellera'' is a herbaceous plant, not a woody one, and its stems do not twine.\n\n==Description==\n''Stellera chamaejasme'' is a [[herbaceous perennial]]. Unbranched stems, 20\u201330&nbsp;cm tall, emerge in a cluster from an underground [[rhizome]]. Narrow, overlapping leaves are borne along the stems. Individual leaves are narrow and pointed, up to 2&nbsp;cm long. The flowers are grouped into rounded tightly packed terminal heads. Flowers lack [[petal]]s, instead having petaloid [[sepal]]s forming a tube up to 1.5&nbsp;cm long with usually five (but possibly four or six) short lobes at the end. The flower colour varies from shades of pink and white to yellow. There are twice as many stamens as calyx lobes, in two series. The ovary has a single chamber ([[locule]]). The fruit is a dry [[drupe]], enclosed by the remains of the calyx.<ref name=Beck94/><ref name=FoC_S/>\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe genus ''Stellera'' was first described by [[Carl Linnaeus]] in 1753.<ref name=IPNI_39323-1/>  He recognized two species: ''Stellera passerina'', now placed in the genus ''[[Thymelaea]]'' as ''[[Thymelaea passerina|T.&nbsp;passerina]]'', and ''Stellera chamaejasme''.<ref name=Linn53/> Many species names were later created in the genus, but all are now usually considered synonyms of other species, including ''S.&nbsp;chamaejasme'',<ref name=TPL_Stellera/> although the ''Flora of China'' states that there are 10 to 12 species.<ref name=FoC_S/>\n\nStudies in 2002 and 2009, based on [[chloroplast DNA]], placed ''Stellera'' in a small group of related genera, either as sister to ''[[Wikstroemia]]'' or embedded within it; however for most genera only one species was included.<ref name=BankFayChas02/><ref name=BeauEdwaMannMaur09/>\n\n{{clade|style=line-height:100%\n|1={{clade\n   |1=''[[Edgeworthia]]''\n   |2={{clade\n      |1={{clade\n         |1=''[[Wikstroemia]]''\n         |2=''Stellera''\n         }}\n      |2={{clade\n         |1=''[[Diarthron]]''\n         |2={{clade\n            |1=''[[Thymelaea]]''\n            |2=''[[Daphne (plant)|Daphne]]''\n            }}\n         }}\n      }}\n   }}\n}}\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\n''Stellera chamaejasme'' is native to northern and western China, Tibet, the Himalayas (Nepal, Bhutan), the state of [[Uttar Pradesh]] in north India, Russia and Mongolia.<ref name=Beck94/><ref name=FoC_Sc/> In China, it is found on sunny dry slopes and sandy places between 2600 and 4200&nbsp;m.<ref name=FoC_Sc/>\n\n==Cultivation==\n''Stellera chamaejasme'' is cultivated as an ornamental plant in [[rock garden]]s and [[alpine house]]s. It is considered difficult to grow, needing a sunny position and gritty soil if grown outside, or a large pot if grown under cover. It is propagated by seed.<ref name=Beck94/>\n\n==Toxicity==\n[[File:Chamaejasme.jpg|thumb|Compared and contrasted: roots of (fancied) human-like form of A: ''Stellera chamaejasme'' and B: ''[[Mandragora officinarum]]'', the fabled ''[[Mandrake]]''. Note also (centre) crown of ''Stellera'', shown bearing a single, herbaceous flowering shoot.]]\n[[File:Stellera chamaejasme blossoming, Longxi, Gansu, China.JPG|thumb|''Stellera chamaejasme'' (in bud) growing in [[Gansu]] [[Provinces of China|province]], Western China, where it has the common name of ''Langdu'' (\u72fc\u6bd2\u82b1) \"wolf poison\" - probably because it was formerly employed as such.]]\n<blockquote>The [[Russian people|Russians]] living in [[Transbaikalia|Dauria]] still hold Stellera in high esteem on account of its root, despite the fact that its violent effects have already dispatched a good many people to the afterlife. This root resembles a crudely-carved human figure to a degree even greater than that of the [ famous ] ''Alraune'' or [[Mandrake|Mandragora]], such that one can often distinguish clearly in its natural form [protuberances resembling] a head, arms and legs; which has led to its being given the most apposite name of ''Muzhik koren'' [\u041c\u0443\u0436\u0438\u043a \u043a\u043e\u0440\u0435\u043d] or \"Man root\" by the Russians. The oldest rootstocks of this plant can reach the size of a large carrot, and [if taken as medicine] produce the most violent effects. Such old roots can produce more than fifty - and sometimes as many as a hundred - flowering shoots, which, crowned with their beautiful and fragrant flowers, give not the least hint of the violent and pernicious effects residing in the root that bore them. The exterior of the flower is usually of a dark reddish-purple, or, more rarely [[sulphur]]-yellow colour; while the interior is white. Add to this the fact that the flowers display, upon opening, a white border and in the middle a red or yellow patch, and the flowers present the most [[Beauty|ravishing]] aspect. The young [[Evenks|Tungus]] boys are in the habit of adorning their bare heads with a kind of hat which they create most artistically by interweaving whole flowering stems of the plant. On this plant one often finds a flower in which two normal flowers seem fused into one, bearing a corolla with nine lobes and eighteen stamens arranged in two rows. [ Translated from the French of a text closely based on the account of [[Prussian]] naturalist and explorer [[Peter Simon Pallas]] ].<ref>[Author anonymous] Histoire des Decouvertes faites par divers savans voyageurs dans plusieurs contr\u00e9es de la Russie & de la Perse, relativement \u00e0 l'Histoire civile & naturelle \u00e0 l'\u00c9conomie rurale, au commerce &c. pub. Aberne, chez Fran\u00e7ois Seizer et Comp., T\u00f4me V, 1787 page 499. Reissued by Nabu Public Domain Reprints, U.S.A.{{vs|date=April 2020}}</ref></blockquote>\nThe plant is virulently poisonous and has caused fatalities both in humans and in [[livestock]]. The powdered roots have been used as a [[pesticide]] and as a [[Fish toxins|fish poison]], and have also been used in small doses as a drastic [[anthelmintic]] for sheep and goats.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Quattrocchi |first1=Umberto |title=CRC World Dictionary of Medicinal and Poisonous Plants: R-Z |date=2012 |publisher=CRC |isbn=978-1-4398-9570-2 |page=395 }}</ref>\nThe plant is common in Western China, where it goes by the common name of ''Langdu'' (\u72fc\u6bd2\u82b1) lit. \"wolf poison\" (\u72fc ''lang'' \"wolf\" + \u6bd2 ''d\u00fa'' \"poison\" + \u82b1 ''hu\u0101'' \"flower\"). It is used as a medicinal herb in China, but can be considered an undesirable element in the flora if it should proliferate to too great an extent, as its large, water-thirsty roots speed up the desertification of prairies.<ref>[Information contained in info. accompanying image of plant in bud on Wikimedia Commons and used on this page.]{{fact|date=April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Chemistry and Properties, Medicinal, Herbicidal etc.==\nThe principal constituents of ''Stellera chamaejasme'' include, among others, [[flavonoid]]s, [[coumarin]]s, [[lignan]]s and [[diterpenoid]]s. The pharmacological properties of these compounds span a wide spectrum, including anti-tumour, anti-viral, anti-bacterial, anti-convulsive, anti-epileptic, insecticidal, anti-inflammatory and immunoregulatory activity. Among the various active compounds, the diterpenoids are widely recognized as the class responsible for the anti-tumor effect. The dried roots of ''S. chamaejasme'' are known as ''Rui-Xiang-Lang-Du'' in [[Traditional Chinese medicine]] in which system this toxic herb is widely used for the treatment of various disorders, being described as \"Effective against dispelling phlegm by water and displaying toxicity against insect pests\".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Li |first1=Xiao-Qin |last2=Rahman |first2=Khalid |last3=Zhu |first3=Jian-Yong |last4=Zhang |first4=Hong |title=Chemical Constituents and Pharmacological Activities of Stellera chamaejasme |journal=Current Pharmaceutical Design |date=8 November 2018 |volume=24 |issue=24 |pages=2825\u20132838 |doi=10.2174/1381612824666180903110802 |pmid=30179119 |url=http://researchonline.ljmu.ac.uk/id/eprint/11490/6/Chemical%20structures.pdf }}</ref>\n\nA scientific paper of 2015 refers to this plant - regarded as a choice and hard-to-grow ornamental by European and American gardeners - as being one of the most toxic of grassland [[weed]]s in the range where it is native and notes that cattle which consume its shoots and flowers may be fatally poisoned. The paper notes further that populations of the plant are in no way endangered, having been flourishing and increasing for some years: this appears to be due not simply to the plant's competing vigorously with other species for water and nutrients, but also to its containing / secreting [[herbicide|herbicidal]] compounds.Water and [[ethanol]] extracts of S. chamaejasme inhibited seed germination and/or seedling growth in no fewer than 13 plant species, and the phytotoxic effects were stronger upon [[dicotyledon]]ous plants than upon [[monocotyledon]]ous plants. The phytotoxic compounds were observed to be liberated particularly by dead or moribund specimens of ''S. chamaejasme'' and to lead to reduced seedling growth in the [[grass]]es ''[[Lolium perenne]]'' <small>L.</small>, ''[[Psathyrostachys juncea]]'' <small>(Fisch.) Nevski</small> and ''[[Bromus inermis]]'' <small>Leyss.</small> and the [[legume]]s ''[[Melilotus suaveolens]]'' <small>Ledeb.</small> (see ''[[Melilotus]]''), ''[[Onobrychis viciifolia]]'' <small>Scop.</small> (sainfoin) and ''[[Medicago sativa]]'' <small>L.</small> (alfalfa). Furthermore, pesticidal properties were confirmed to be present in ''S. chameajasme'': the ethanolic extract of S. chameajasme strongly inhabited the growth of the following insect pests: the butterfly ''[[Pieris rapae]]'', the aphid ''[[Myzus persicae]]'' and the corn-borer moth ''[[Ostrinia furnacalis]]'', and showed contact and oral toxicities against two other stem-borer moths which are pests of [[rice]]: ''[[Sesamia inferens]]'' and ''[[Chilo suppressalis]]''. <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Yan |first1=Zhiqiang |last2=Zeng |first2=Liming |last3=Jin |first3=Hui |last4=Qin |first4=Bo |title=Potential ecological roles of flavonoids from Stellera chamaejasme |journal=Plant Signaling & Behavior |date=7 April 2015 |volume=10 |issue=3 |pages=e1001225 |doi=10.1080/15592324.2014.1001225 |pmid=25848835 |pmc=4622577 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=BankFayChas02>{{Citation |last1=van der Bank |first1=Michelle |last2=Fay |first2=Michael F. |last3=Chase |first3=Mark W. |date=2002 |title=Molecular Phylogenetics of Thymelaeaceae with particular reference to African and Australian genera |journal=Taxon |volume=51 |issue=2 |pages=329\u2013339 |jstor=1554930 |lastauthoramp=yes |doi=10.2307/1554901 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=BeauEdwaMannMaur09>{{Citation |last1=Beaumont |first1=Angela J. |last2=Edwards |first2=Trevor J. |last3=Manning |first3=John |last4=Maurin |first4=Olivier |last5=Rautenbach |first5=Marline |last6=Motsi |first6=Moleboheng C. |last7=Fay |first7=Michael F. |last8=Chase |first8=Mark W. |last9=Van Der Bank |first9=Michelle |date=2009 |title=Gnidia (Thymelaeaceae) is not monophyletic: taxonomic implications for Thymelaeoideae and a partial new generic taxonomy for ''Gnidia'' |journal=Botanical Journal of the Linnean Society |volume=160 |issue=4 |pages=402\u2013417 |doi=10.1111/j.1095-8339.2009.00988.x |lastauthoramp=yes |doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Beck94>{{Citation |year=1994 |editor-last=Beckett |editor-first=K. |title=Encyclopaedia of Alpines : Volume 2 (L\u2013Z) \n|contribution=Stellera |page=1285 |location=Pershore, UK |publisher=AGS Publications |isbn=978-0-900048-62-3 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=FoC_S>{{citation |first1=Yinzheng |last1=Wang |first2=Michael G. |last2=Gilbert |contribution=Stellaria |contribution-url=http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=2&taxon_id=131303 |accessdate=2017-11-26 |editor-last=Wu |editor-first=Zhengyi |editor2-last=Raven |editor2-first=Peter H. |editor3-last=Hong |editor3-first=Deyuan <!--|date=1994 onwards--> |title=Flora of China ''(online)'' |publisher=eFloras.org |url=http://www.efloras.org/flora_page.aspx?flora_id=2 |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=FoC_Sc>{{citation |first1=Yinzheng |last1=Wang |first2=Michael G. |last2=Gilbert |contribution=Stellaria chamaejasme |contribution-url=http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=2&taxon_id=200014523 |accessdate=2017-11-26 |editor-last=Wu |editor-first=Zhengyi |editor2-last=Raven |editor2-first=Peter H. |editor3-last=Hong |editor3-first=Deyuan <!--|date=1994 onwards--> |title=Flora of China ''(online)'' |publisher=eFloras.org |url=http://www.efloras.org/flora_page.aspx?flora_id=2 |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=IPNI_39323-1>{{citation |title=Plant Name Details for ''Stellera''&#32;L. |work=[[International Plant Names Index|The International Plant Names Index]] |url=http://www.ipni.org/ipni/idPlantNameSearch.do?id=39323-1 |accessdate=2017-11-26 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Linn53>{{Citation |last1=Linnaeus |first1=Carl |date=1753 |contribution=Stellera |title=Species Plantarum |volume=1 |page=559 |location=Stockholm, Sweden |publisher=Laurentius Salvius |language=Latin |contribution-url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/358577 |accessdate=2017-11-26}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=TPL_Stellera>{{citation |title=Search results for ''Stellera''|work=The Plant List |url=http://www.theplantlist.org/tpl1.1/search?q=Stellera |accessdate=2017-11-26 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q3487244}}\n\n[[Category:Thymelaeoideae]]\n[[Category:Monotypic Malvales genera]]\n[[Category:Poisonous plants]]\n[[Category:Flora of temperate Asia]]\n[[Category:Medicinal plants of Asia]]\n[[Category:Garden plants of Asia]]\n[[Category:Flora of Central Asia]]\n[[Category:Flora of Russia]]\n[[Category:Flora of Siberia]]\n[[Category:Flora of China]]\n\n\n{{Thymelaeaceae-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n|image = Stellera chamaejasme 2.jpg\n|display_parents = 2\n|genus = Stellera\n|parent_authority = L.<ref name=IPNI_39323-1/> \n|species = chamaejasme\n|authority = L.<ref name=TPL_Stellera/>\n}}\n\n'''''Stellera''''' is a [[genus]] of [[flowering plant]] in the family [[Thymelaeaceae]], with a single species '''''Stellera chamaejasme''''',<ref name=TPL_Stellera/> found in mountainous regions of [[Central Asia]], [[China]], [[Siberia]] and [[South Asia]]. ''S.&nbsp;chamaejasme'' is a herbaceous [[perennial]] plant with heads of white, pink or yellow flowers, grown as an ornamental plant in [[rock garden]]s and [[alpine house]]s, but considered a [[weed]] playing a r\u00f4le in the [[desertification]] of grasslands in parts of its native range. Like many others of its family, it is a [[poisonous plant]] with medicinal and other useful properties.\n\n==Scientific Name==\n\n[[File:Pink jasmine bush.jpg|thumb|''[[Jasminum polyanthum]]'' in bloom, showing wine-red exteriors of corollas reminiscent of those of ''Stellera'' (re. species name ''chamaejasme'' i.e. \"ground jasmine\").]]\nThe [[Monotypic taxon|monotypic genus]] ''Stellera'' (not to be confused with the entirely unrelated ''[[Stellaria]]'') commemorates [[Georg Wilhelm Steller]] (St\u00f6ller), while the specific epithet ''chamaejasme'' is a rendering into botanical Latin orthography of the Greek \u03c7\u03b1\u03bc\u03b1\u03af ''khamai'' \"(down) on the ground\" and \u03b9\u03b1\u03c3\u03bc\u03b5 ''iasme'' \"[[jasmine]]\". The name in its entirety thus means \"Steller's plant that resembles a kind of jasmine (that creeps) on the ground\". The name of the species is doubly apt, as not only is the flower of ''Stellera chamaejasme'' fragrant like that of jasmine, but it also has a wine-red exterior, like that of certain species of jasmine e.g. Common jasmine ''[[Jasminum officinale]]'' and the Chinese species ''[[Jasminum polyanthum]]''. Unlike jasmine, however, ''Stellera'' is a herbaceous plant, not a woody one, and its stems do not twine.\n\n==Description==\n''Stellera chamaejasme'' is a [[herbaceous perennial]]. Unbranched stems, 20\u201330&nbsp;cm tall, emerge in a cluster from an underground [[rhizome]]. Narrow, overlapping leaves are borne along the stems. Individual leaves are narrow and pointed, up to 2&nbsp;cm long. The flowers are grouped into rounded tightly packed terminal heads. Flowers lack [[petal]]s, instead having petaloid [[sepal]]s forming a tube up to 1.5&nbsp;cm long with usually five (but possibly four or six) short lobes at the end. The flower colour varies from shades of pink and white to yellow. There are twice as many stamens as calyx lobes, in two series. The ovary has a single chamber ([[locule]]). The fruit is a dry [[drupe]], enclosed by the remains of the calyx.<ref name=Beck94/><ref name=FoC_S/>\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe genus ''Stellera'' was first described by [[Carl Linnaeus]] in 1753.<ref name=IPNI_39323-1/>  He recognized two species: ''Stellera passerina'', now placed in the genus ''[[Thymelaea]]'' as ''[[Thymelaea passerina|T.&nbsp;passerina]]'', and ''Stellera chamaejasme''.<ref name=Linn53/> Many species names were later created in the genus, but all are now usually considered synonyms of other species, including ''S.&nbsp;chamaejasme'',<ref name=TPL_Stellera/> although the ''Flora of China'' states that there are 10 to 12 species.<ref name=FoC_S/>\n\nStudies in 2002 and 2009, based on [[chloroplast DNA]], placed ''Stellera'' in a small group of related genera, either as sister to ''[[Wikstroemia]]'' or embedded within it; however for most genera only one species was included.<ref name=BankFayChas02/><ref name=BeauEdwaMannMaur09/>\n\n{{clade|style=line-height:100%\n|1={{clade\n   |1=''[[Edgeworthia]]''\n   |2={{clade\n      |1={{clade\n         |1=''[[Wikstroemia]]''\n         |2=''Stellera''\n         }}\n      |2={{clade\n         |1=''[[Diarthron]]''\n         |2={{clade\n            |1=''[[Thymelaea]]''\n            |2=''[[Daphne (plant)|Daphne]]''\n            }}\n         }}\n      }}\n   }}\n}}\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\n''Stellera chamaejasme'' is native to northern and western China, Tibet, the Himalayas (Nepal, Bhutan), the state of [[Uttar Pradesh]] in north India, Russia and Mongolia.<ref name=Beck94/><ref name=FoC_Sc/> In China, it is found on sunny dry slopes and sandy places between 2600 and 4200&nbsp;m.<ref name=FoC_Sc/>\n\n==Cultivation==\n''Stellera chamaejasme'' is cultivated as an ornamental plant in [[rock garden]]s and [[alpine house]]s. It is considered difficult to grow, needing a sunny position and gritty soil if grown outside, or a large pot if grown under cover. It is propagated by seed.<ref name=Beck94/>\n\n==Toxicity==\n[[File:Chamaejasme.jpg|thumb|Compared and contrasted: roots of (fancied) human-like form of A: ''Stellera chamaejasme'' and B: ''[[Mandragora officinarum]]'', the fabled ''[[Mandrake]]''. Note also (centre) crown of ''Stellera'', shown bearing a single, herbaceous flowering shoot.]]\n[[File:Stellera chamaejasme blossoming, Longxi, Gansu, China.JPG|thumb|''Stellera chamaejasme'' (in bud) growing in [[Gansu]] [[Provinces of China|province]], Western China, where it has the common name of ''Langdu'' (\u72fc\u6bd2\u82b1) \"wolf poison\" - probably because it was formerly employed as such.]]\n<blockquote>The [[Russian people|Russians]] living in [[Transbaikalia|Dauria]] still hold Stellera in high esteem on account of its root, despite the fact that its violent effects have already dispatched a good many people to the afterlife. This root resembles a crudely-carved human figure to a degree even greater than that of the [ famous ] ''Alraune'' or [[Mandrake|Mandragora]], such that one can often distinguish clearly in its natural form [protuberances resembling] a head, arms and legs; which has led to its being given the most apposite name of ''Muzhik koren'' [\u041c\u0443\u0436\u0438\u043a \u043a\u043e\u0440\u0435\u043d] or \"Man root\" by the Russians. The oldest rootstocks of this plant can reach the size of a large carrot, and [if taken as medicine] produce the most violent effects. Such old roots can produce more than fifty - and sometimes as many as a hundred - flowering shoots, which, crowned with their beautiful and fragrant flowers, give not the least hint of the violent and pernicious effects residing in the root that bore them. The exterior of the flower is usually of a dark reddish-purple, or, more rarely [[sulphur]]-yellow colour; while the interior is white. Add to this the fact that the flowers display, upon opening, a white border and in the middle a red or yellow patch, and the flowers present the most [[Beauty|ravishing]] aspect. The young [[Evenks|Tungus]] boys are in the habit of adorning their bare heads with a kind of hat which they create most artistically by interweaving whole flowering stems of the plant. On this plant one often finds a flower in which two normal flowers seem fused into one, bearing a corolla with nine lobes and eighteen stamens arranged in two rows. [ Translated from the French of a text closely based on the account of [[Prussian]] naturalist and explorer [[Peter Simon Pallas]] ].<ref>[Author anonymous] Histoire des Decouvertes faites par divers savans voyageurs dans plusieurs contr\u00e9es de la Russie & de la Perse, relativement \u00e0 l'Histoire civile & naturelle \u00e0 l'\u00c9conomie rurale, au commerce &c. pub. Aberne, chez Fran\u00e7ois Seizer et Comp., T\u00f4me V, 1787 page 499. Reissued by Nabu Public Domain Reprints, U.S.A.{{vs|date=April 2020}}</ref></blockquote>\nThe plant is virulently poisonous and has caused fatalities both in humans and in [[livestock]]. The powdered roots have been used as a [[pesticide]] and as a [[Fish toxins|fish poison]], and have also been used in small doses as a drastic [[anthelmintic]] for sheep and goats.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Quattrocchi |first1=Umberto |title=CRC World Dictionary of Medicinal and Poisonous Plants: R-Z |date=2012 |publisher=CRC |isbn=978-1-4398-9570-2 |page=395 }}</ref>\nThe plant is common in Western China, where it goes by the common name of ''Langdu'' (\u72fc\u6bd2\u82b1) lit. \"wolf poison\" (\u72fc ''lang'' \"wolf\" + \u6bd2 ''d\u00fa'' \"poison\" + \u82b1 ''hu\u0101'' \"flower\"). It is used as a medicinal herb in China, but can be considered an undesirable element in the flora if it should proliferate to too great an extent, as its large, water-thirsty roots speed up the desertification of prairies.<ref>[Information contained in info. accompanying image of plant in bud on Wikimedia Commons and used on this page.]{{fact|date=April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Chemistry and Properties, Medicinal, Herbicidal etc.==\nThe principal constituents of ''Stellera chamaejasme'' include, among others, [[flavonoid]]s, [[coumarin]]s, [[lignan]]s and [[diterpenoid]]s. The pharmacological properties of these compounds span a wide spectrum, including anti-tumour, anti-viral, anti-bacterial, anti-convulsive, anti-epileptic, insecticidal, anti-inflammatory and immunoregulatory activity. Among the various active compounds, the diterpenoids are widely recognized as the class responsible for the anti-tumor effect. The dried roots of ''S. chamaejasme'' are known as ''Rui-Xiang-Lang-Du'' in [[Traditional Chinese medicine]] in which system this toxic herb is widely used for the treatment of various disorders, being described as \"Effective against dispelling phlegm by water and displaying toxicity against insect pests\".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Li |first1=Xiao-Qin |last2=Rahman |first2=Khalid |last3=Zhu |first3=Jian-Yong |last4=Zhang |first4=Hong |title=Chemical Constituents and Pharmacological Activities of Stellera chamaejasme |journal=Current Pharmaceutical Design |date=8 November 2018 |volume=24 |issue=24 |pages=2825\u20132838 |doi=10.2174/1381612824666180903110802 |pmid=30179119 |url=http://researchonline.ljmu.ac.uk/id/eprint/11490/6/Chemical%20structures.pdf }}</ref>\n\nA scientific paper of 2015 refers to this plant - regarded as a choice and hard-to-grow ornamental by European and American gardeners - as being one of the most toxic of grassland [[weed]]s in the range where it is native and notes that cattle which consume its shoots and flowers may be fatally poisoned. The paper notes further that populations of the plant are in no way endangered, having been flourishing and increasing for some years: this appears to be due not simply to the plant's competing vigorously with other species for water and nutrients, but also to its containing / secreting [[herbicide|herbicidal]] compounds.Water and [[ethanol]] extracts of S. chamaejasme inhibited seed germination and/or seedling growth in no fewer than 13 plant species, and the phytotoxic effects were stronger upon [[dicotyledon]]ous plants than upon [[monocotyledon]]ous plants. The phytotoxic compounds were observed to be liberated particularly by dead or moribund specimens of ''S. chamaejasme'' and to lead to reduced seedling growth in the [[grass]]es ''[[Lolium perenne]]'' <small>L.</small>, ''[[Psathyrostachys juncea]]'' <small>(Fisch.) Nevski</small> and ''[[Bromus inermis]]'' <small>Leyss.</small> and the [[legume]]s ''[[Melilotus suaveolens]]'' <small>Ledeb.</small> (see ''[[Melilotus]]''), ''[[Onobrychis viciifolia]]'' <small>Scop.</small> (sainfoin) and ''[[Medicago sativa]]'' <small>L.</small> (alfalfa). Furthermore, pesticidal properties were confirmed to be present in ''S. chameajasme'': the ethanolic extract of S. chameajasme strongly inhabited the growth of the following insect pests: the butterfly ''[[Pieris rapae]]'', the aphid ''[[Myzus persicae]]'' and the corn-borer moth ''[[Ostrinia furnacalis]]'', and showed contact and oral toxicities against two other stem-borer moths which are pests of [[rice]]: ''[[Sesamia inferens]]'' and ''[[Chilo suppressalis]]''. <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Yan |first1=Zhiqiang |last2=Zeng |first2=Liming |last3=Jin |first3=Hui |last4=Qin |first4=Bo |title=Potential ecological roles of flavonoids from Stellera chamaejasme |journal=Plant Signaling & Behavior |date=7 April 2015 |volume=10 |issue=3 |pages=e1001225 |doi=10.1080/15592324.2014.1001225 |pmid=25848835 |pmc=4622577 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=BankFayChas02>{{Citation |last1=van der Bank |first1=Michelle |last2=Fay |first2=Michael F. |last3=Chase |first3=Mark W. |date=2002 |title=Molecular Phylogenetics of Thymelaeaceae with particular reference to African and Australian genera |journal=Taxon |volume=51 |issue=2 |pages=329\u2013339 |jstor=1554930 |lastauthoramp=yes |doi=10.2307/1554901 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=BeauEdwaMannMaur09>{{Citation |last1=Beaumont |first1=Angela J. |last2=Edwards |first2=Trevor J. |last3=Manning |first3=John |last4=Maurin |first4=Olivier |last5=Rautenbach |first5=Marline |last6=Motsi |first6=Moleboheng C. |last7=Fay |first7=Michael F. |last8=Chase |first8=Mark W. |last9=Van Der Bank |first9=Michelle |date=2009 |title=Gnidia (Thymelaeaceae) is not monophyletic: taxonomic implications for Thymelaeoideae and a partial new generic taxonomy for ''Gnidia'' |journal=Botanical Journal of the Linnean Society |volume=160 |issue=4 |pages=402\u2013417 |doi=10.1111/j.1095-8339.2009.00988.x |lastauthoramp=yes |doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Beck94>{{Citation |year=1994 |editor-last=Beckett |editor-first=K. |title=Encyclopaedia of Alpines : Volume 2 (L\u2013Z) \n|contribution=Stellera |page=1285 |location=Pershore, UK |publisher=AGS Publications |isbn=978-0-900048-62-3 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=FoC_S>{{citation |first1=Yinzheng |last1=Wang |first2=Michael G. |last2=Gilbert |contribution=Stellaria |contribution-url=http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=2&taxon_id=131303 |accessdate=2017-11-26 |editor-last=Wu |editor-first=Zhengyi |editor2-last=Raven |editor2-first=Peter H. |editor3-last=Hong |editor3-first=Deyuan <!--|date=1994 onwards--> |title=Flora of China ''(online)'' |publisher=eFloras.org |url=http://www.efloras.org/flora_page.aspx?flora_id=2 |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=FoC_Sc>{{citation |first1=Yinzheng |last1=Wang |first2=Michael G. |last2=Gilbert |contribution=Stellaria chamaejasme |contribution-url=http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=2&taxon_id=200014523 |accessdate=2017-11-26 |editor-last=Wu |editor-first=Zhengyi |editor2-last=Raven |editor2-first=Peter H. |editor3-last=Hong |editor3-first=Deyuan <!--|date=1994 onwards--> |title=Flora of China ''(online)'' |publisher=eFloras.org |url=http://www.efloras.org/flora_page.aspx?flora_id=2 |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=IPNI_39323-1>{{citation |title=Plant Name Details for ''Stellera''&#32;L. |work=[[International Plant Names Index|The International Plant Names Index]] |url=http://www.ipni.org/ipni/idPlantNameSearch.do?id=39323-1 |accessdate=2017-11-26 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Linn53>{{Citation |last1=Linnaeus |first1=Carl |date=1753 |contribution=Stellera |title=Species Plantarum |volume=1 |page=559 |location=Stockholm, Sweden |publisher=Laurentius Salvius |language=Latin |contribution-url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/358577 |accessdate=2017-11-26}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=TPL_Stellera>{{citation |title=Search results for ''Stellera''|work=The Plant List |url=http://www.theplantlist.org/tpl1.1/search?q=Stellera |accessdate=2017-11-26 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q3487244}}\n\n[[Category:Thymelaeoideae]]\n[[Category:Monotypic Malvales genera]]\n[[Category:Poisonous plants]]\n[[Category:Flora of temperate Asia]]\n[[Category:Medicinal plants of Asia]]\n[[Category:Garden plants of Asia]]\n[[Category:Flora of Central Asia]]\n[[Category:Flora of Russia]]\n[[Category:Flora of Siberia]\n[[Category:Flora of China]]\n\n\n{{Thymelaeaceae-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Flobbadob", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stellera"}
{"title_page": "Miami Dade College", "text_new": "{{Infobox university\n| name = Miami Dade College\n| former_names = Dade Junior College<br />Miami Dade Junior College<br />Miami Dade Community College\n| other_name = Dade\n| image = Miami Dade College logo.svg\n| established = {{start date and age|1959}}\n| type = [[Public College]]\n| endowment = $491.7 million (2019)<ref>As of June 30, 2019. {{cite web |url=https://www.nacubo.org/-/media/Nacubo/Documents/EndowmentFiles/2019-NTSE-Endowment-Market-Values--FINAL-January-30-2020.ashx|title=U.S. and Canadian Institutions Listed by Fiscal Year (FY) 2019 Endowment Market Value and Change in Endowment Market Value from FY 2018 to FY 2019 |publisher=National Association of College and University Business Officers and TIAA |access-date=February 28, 2020}}</ref>\n| president = Rolando Montoya (interim)\n| city = [[Miami]]\n| state = [[Florida]]\n| country = United States\n| campus = Urban\n| students = 165,000 (2014\u201315)\n| faculty = 6,500<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/main/about/facts_in_brief.asp|title=Page Not Found - Miami Dade College|work=mdc.edu|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n| colors = Blue & Gray {{color box|#0033a0}} {{color box|#737b82}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/mktg/logos.html|title=MDC Logo Guidelines|publisher=Miami Dade College|accessdate=March 10, 2016}}</ref>\n| mascot = Finn the Shark<ref>[https://news.mdc.edu/finn-wins Finn Wins!]</ref>\n| website = [http://www.mdc.edu/ www.mdc.edu]|\n}}\n\n'''Miami Dade College''' ('''Miami Dade,''' '''MDC''' or '''Dade''')<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/30/us/30dade.html|title=Eduardo J. Padr\u00f3n, the college's president since 1995.|last=|first=|date=|work=A Community College in Florida Works to Attract the Poor and the Presidential|access-date=}}</ref> is a [[public college]] in [[Miami]], [[Florida]]. Founded in 1959, it has a total of eight [[campus]]es and twenty-one [[outreach]] centers throughout [[Miami-Dade County]]. It is the largest college in the Florida College System with over 165,000 students <ref>{{cite web |title=Miami-Dade College (U.S) |url=https://fotw.info/flags/us_u_mmd.html |website=FOTW \"Flags of the world\" |accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Padr\u00f3n|first=Eduardo J.|date=June 2013|title=Increasing the Relevance of Curricular and Student Services in the Urban Community College|journal=New Directions for Community Colleges |volume=2013 |issue=162 |pages=63\u201373 |doi=10.1002/cc.20060 |issn=0194-3081}}</ref> and the second-largest college or university in the United States. Miami Dade College enrolls a significantly larger amount of Hispanic students each year compared to other colleges and universities in the state of Florida.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/programs/digest/d17/tables/dt17_312.40.asp|title=Digest of Education Statistics, 2017|website=nces.ed.gov|language=EN|access-date=2019-12-04}}</ref> Miami Dade College has 8 different campuses that make up the college and the first being the North Campus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.miamitodaynews.com/2019/11/12/rolando-montoya-interim-college-president-sees-tech-courses-demand-soar/|title=Rolando Montoya: Interim college president sees tech courses demand soar|date=2019-11-12|website=Miami Today|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-04}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\nInitially established on the farm of a county high school, Dade County Junior College\u2014as it was formerly known\u2014had its modest beginnings. Like most organizations at the time, it was a segregated institution. It wasn't until 1962 that [[Desegregation in the United States|desegregation]] took full effect; black and white students could share full schedules together. In 1963, the ballsack first new building was constructed, and Peter Masiko would become president for the next 18 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.linccweb.org/webscripts/lwauth.aspx?calling_system=ezproxy&institute=flcc1600&url=https://infoweb.newsbank.com/apps/news/document-view?p=AWNB&t=&sort=YMD_date:A&fld-base-0=alltext&maxresults=20&val-base-0=%20%22Dade%20County%20Junior%20College%22&docref=news/0EB360A06EE6EE4D|title=LINCCWeb Catalog Search|website=www.linccweb.org|access-date=2020-02-18}}</ref> As the years progressed, more campuses began opening across the county: the Kendall Campus and Wolfson Campus.\n\nInitially, the college had an open admissions policy, meaning anyone who could afford to pay was allowed to study at the campus. Due to this, the college aimed to improve its academic stance among alumni. To encourage this movement, a Medical Center was built for students in [[Allied health professions|Allied Health]] and Nursing ([[Registered nurse|RN]]) programs. As the number of Cuban exiles and refugees began to rise in 1980, and [[Outreach|outreach center]] was built in the city of [[Hialeah]]. This allowed refugees and immigrants educational opportunities that they wouldn't be able to achieve otherwise. Another outreach center, the InterAmerican center, was built to accommodate [[bilingual education]]. The Homestead Campus was built in 1990 in [[Homestead, Florida|Homestead]] to relieve the concerns of students having to drive to the Kendall Campus In Miami. In the mid-1990s, the college began to rely heavily on the Miami Dade College Foundation as the [[Florida Legislature|Florida legislature]] reduced the state's education budget. The college also had to figure out new ways of recruiting students and it began its \"Successful Alumni\" campaign in the late 1990s, marketing the success of the college's alumni to local prospective students.\n\nBeginning in 2001, the college implemented a strategic plan to revamp the college and its recruiting goals. In 2002, the college disbanded its [[Honors colleges and programs|Honors Program]] and created The Honors College for talented high school graduates.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mdc.edu/about/history.aspx|title=History of MDC {{!}} Miami Dade College|website=www.mdc.edu|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref> The [[Honors colleges and programs|Honors College]] is a representation of Miami Dade College's most [[Academically gifted|academically-gifted]] students in different fields and was originally based on the three larger campuses (Wolfson, Kendall, and North).In 2006, Miami Dade College surpassed 1.5 million students enrolled throughout its history. In 2007, The Honors College expanded into the InterAmerican Campus with The Honors College Dual Language Honors Program to tailor to the needs of the growing Spanish-speaking population in the [[United States]] as well as abroad. The Dual Language Honors Program opened its doors to bilingual students who wish to continue their careers with professional fluency in the English and Spanish languages. In 2009, The MDC Honors College Dual Language Program earned the merit of Innovation of the Year in the Learning and Teaching Department from the League for Innovation. In 2018, Miami Dade was awarded and recognized for its path to economic and social mobility by the Aspen Institute. The award received was the $1 million Aspen Prize.\n\nOn February 1, 2019, [[Eduardo J. Padr\u00f3n|Eduardo Padron]], Miami Dade College President, announced that he plans to retire from the position he has held since 1995.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Campus\n! Year opened\n! Students\n! Size\n! Location\n|-\n| Carrie P. Meek Entrepreneurial Education Center<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/north/campus-information/eec.aspx|title=Carrie P. Meek Entrepreneurial Education Center - North Campus - Miami Dade College|work=mdc.edu|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n| 1989\n| 2,500+\n| NA\n| [[Liberty City (Miami)|Liberty City]]\n|-\n| Hialeah Campus<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/hialeah/|title=Miami Dade College - Hialeah Campus|work=mdc.edu|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n| 1980<br />2005 (Official designation)\n| NA\n| 8 acres\n| [[Hialeah, Florida|Hialeah]]\n|-\n| Homestead Campus<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/homestead/|title=Homestead Campus|work=mdc.edu|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n| 1990\n| \n| 18 acres\n| [[Homestead, Florida|Downtown Homestead]]\n|-\n| Eduardo J. Padron Campus<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/padron/|title=Padron Campus Campus|work=mdc.edu|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n| 1986<br />2001 (Official designation)\n| 6,500\n| 4 acres\n| [[Little Havana]], Miami\n|-\n| Kendall Campus<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/kendall/|title=Kendall Campus|work=mdc.edu|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n| 1967\n| 66,500\n| 185 acres\n| [[Kendall, Florida|Kendall]], Miami\n|-\n| MDC-West<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/west/|title=MDC West - Miami Dade College|work=mdc.edu|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n| 2005\n| NA\n| 10 acres\n| [[Doral, Florida|Doral]]\n|-\n| Medical Campus<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/medical/|title=Medical Campus|work=mdc.edu|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n| 1977\n| NA\n| 4.3 acres\n|  (Miami)|[[Allapattah]], Miami\n|-\n| North Campus<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/north/about.asp|title=About North Campus - Miami-Dade College - North Campus|work=mdc.edu|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n| 1960\n| 41,000\n| 245 acres\n| [[Westview, Florida|Westview]]\n|-\n| '''[[Wolfson Campus]]<br />(Main campus)'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/wolfson/campus-information/default.aspx|title=Campus Information - Wolfson Campus - Miami Dade College|work=mdc.edu|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n| '''1970'''\n| '''27,000'''\n| '''15 acres'''\n| '''[[Downtown Miami]]'''\n|-\n|}\nMiami Dade College has seven campuses and two centers, with its main campus being the Wolfson Campus in downtown [[Miami]].These eight campuses and various outreach centers are located throughout [[Miami-Dade County, Florida|Miami-Dade County]]. The Honors College is currently represented on four campuses, with a new [[Multilingualism|bilingual]] program (English-Spanish) at the Padron Campus.  All campuses have different schools for various disciplines (engineering, business, etc.). Some campuses also operate [[Dual enrollment|dual-enrollment]] programs for high school students. Most campuses also have College Preparatory or English as a Second Language ([[ESL]]) courses that help students pass the Computerized Placement Test (CPT) that is required for admittance and proves prospective students are qualified to take college-level mathematics and [[English studies|English]] courses\n\n=== North Campus  ===\n[[File:MDC north campush science.jpg|thumb|Miami Dade North Campus Science Complex|alt=|251x251px]]North Campus has specialized programs that train future firefighters, police officers, and Emergency medical service personnels. It also has a School of Entertainment and Design Technology. This campus partners with Florida Agricultural and Mechanical University (FAMU) for engineering programs. The North Campus operates the Carrie Meek Entrepreneurial Education Center in Liberty City. The campus also offers a Bachelor in Applied Science degree in Public Safety that is housed within the School of Justice.\n\n=== Kendall Campus ===\nKendall Campus houses the college's athletic teams. The 185-acre campus opened in 1967.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/kendall/campus-information/default.aspx|title=Campus Information - Kendall Campus {{!}} Miami Dade College|website=www.mdc.edu|access-date=2019-02-08}}</ref> It is home to the Honors College and the Miami Dade College Foundation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/kendall/|title=Miami Dade College Kendall Campus|last=|first=|date=|website=mdc.edu|access-date=}}</ref> Apart from the Latin Jazz experience being held at the Kendall Campus they also allow student to receive community service hours that can be apply to their degree through the CSI and Procedural Justice Camps for the youth, including those with disabilities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/article230780629.html|title=Camps at college mean summertime fun, and, yes, some learning|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>[[File:Kendall Campus - Building R.jpg|thumb|Kendall Campus - Building R|alt=|left|267x267px]]\n\n=== Wolfson Campus ===\nThe Wolfson Campus was opened in 1970 and is the only comprehensive urban campus in the city. Located within the city's financial, governmental, technological and cultural hubs, Wolfson educates over 27,000 students each year. MDC's Wolfson Campus program is designed Accelerate, Retain, Complete with Opportunities and Support and is aimed at creating a support network for 600 STEM students.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/education/article41551710.html|title=Miami Herald|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Each year, this campus hosts the [[Miami Book Fair International]], the nation's largest literary festival.The Miami Culinary Institute of Miami Dade College is located in this campus where it offers a Chefs Apprentice Program, Culinary Arts Management and an Associate in science. It is a multi-million dollar architectural project.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/culinary/programs.aspx|title=Programs {{!}} Miami Culinary Institute {{!}} Miami Dade College|website=www.mdc.edu|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref>\n\nThe goal is to keep Hispanic and other low-income high-need students engaged in the program. The campus has two art galleries, a library, and two computer courtyards. The [[Miami Dade College (Wolfson Campus)|Wolfson Campus]] also has business and paralegal studies programs.[[File:Building REVEST Program.jpg|thumb|189x189px|Hialeah Outreach Center, located at 3680 W 16 Ave Hialeah, Fl 33012. House of MDC REVEST Program.|alt=]]\n[[File:Center Pardon Campus.jpg|thumb|251x251px|Center of Flags in the Padr\u00f3n Campus]]\n\n=== Medical Center ===\nMiami Dade College opened its medical campus in 1977.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/medical/campus-information/|title=Campus Information - Medical Campus {{!}} Miami Dade College|website=www.mdc.edu|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref> It is located in Miami's Medical District near downtown Miami, trains students in the Nursing (BSN/RN) and Allied Health fields, completing the Associate in Applied Science and school degree that will allow them immediate entry into health professions. The Medical Campus also offers bachelor's degrees.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/academics/programs/bachelors.aspx|title=Bachelor's Degree Programs {{!}} Academics {{!}} Miami Dade College|website=www.mdc.edu|access-date=2019-02-08}}</ref> The campus shares its complex with The University of Miami's School of Medicine, [[Jackson Memorial Hospital]], Veterans Administration Hospital and Miami Dade College Public Health Service<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/about/campuses.aspx|title=Campuses {{!}} Miami Dade College|website=www.mdc.edu|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref>\n\n=== Homestead Campus ===\nThe Homestead Campus contains the college's aviation program, one of thirteen schools in the nation accredited ATC-CTI (Air Traffic Control Collegiate Training Initiative) status by the [[Federal Aviation Administration]] (FAA). It also possesses, in addition to the Medical Campus, the renowned Benjamin Leon School of Nursing that has trained over fifty percent of nurses in Miami-Dade County.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/nursing/|title=School of Nursing {{!}} Miami Dade College|website=www.mdc.edu|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref>[[File:Picture of the Eduardo J Padron campus.jpg|thumb|Building 6 that is located on the Eduardo J. Padron campus of Miami Dade College, minutes from downtown, Miami. |alt=|left]]\n\n=== Eduardo J. Padr\u00f3n Campus ===\n[[Eduardo J. Padr\u00f3n]] Campus is the sixth campus created by Miami Dade College. It was previously known as the InterAmerican campus, but was later changed to Eduardo J Padr\u00f3n in honor of MDC's president being with the college for 50 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.mdc.edu/press_release/miami-dade-college-to-rename-its-interamerican-campus-the-eduardo-j-padron-campus-on-may-17/|title=Miami Dade College to Rename its InterAmerican Campus the Eduardo J. Padr\u00f3n Campus on May 17|website=MDC News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> This campus was first created in 1972, but didn't get the status of a \"campus\" til March 27, 2001.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mdc.edu/padron/campus-information/|title=Campus Information - Eduardo J. Padr\u00f3n Campus {{!}} Miami Dade College|website=www.mdc.edu|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> This campus contains the School of Education which offers Bachelor of Science (BS) degrees.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/iac/|title=Miami Dade College Inter American Campus|last=|first=|date=|website=mdc. edu|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== New World School of the Arts ===\nThe [[New World School of the Arts]] is both a high school and a college that focuses on visual arts, theatre, dance, and music. Admission requirements include an audition or review of the applicant's art portfolio. Aside from New World School of the Arts and the MEEC, there are nineteen other MDC outreach centers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/main/campus%5Ffinder/outreach%5Fcenters/|title=Outreach Centers|work=mdc.edu|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nwsa.mdc.edu|title=New World School Of The Arts|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Hialeah Campus ==\n[[File:Miami Dade Hialeah.jpg|alt=|thumb|This is a night view of the Hialeah Miami Dade Campus|279x279px]]The [[Hialeah, Florida|Hialeah]] Campus is a former extension of the North Campus, houses a large and comprehensive English language training program for \nspeakers of other languages in various instructional formats. Construction of a 1,000 car parking garage and a new building housing classrooms, science labs, and student services was completed in 2014.The out doors of the campus has palm trees with a sufficient amount of chairs for students waiting on their next class or for eating some food. The inside of the campus may seem small but has four floors on one side of the building and three floors on the other side of the building. The Hialeah Campus offers associate programs and the Bachelor of Applied Science in Supervision and Management.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/hialeah/campus-information/default.aspx|title=Campus Information - Hialeah Campus - Miami Dade College|website=www.mdc.edu|access-date=2019-02-08}}</ref>\n\n=== West Campus ===\nWest Campus opened in March 2006 for students residing in or near Doral.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/west/campus-information/default.aspx|title=Campus Information - MDC West - Miami Dade College|website=www.mdc.edu|access-date=2019-02-08}}</ref> The campus had begun construction on a new 5 story garage in January 2012; in October of the same year, the garage collapsed, this collapse resulted in the death of 4 construction workers. In 2015 the contractors and subcontractors involved in the project reached an agreement with Miami Dade College in the amount of 33.5 million dollars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/community/miami-dade/doral/article20700564.html|title=Miami Dade College wins $33 million settlement over collapsed parking garage|last=Teproff|first=Carli|date=May 11, 2015|website=The Miami Herald|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref> This Fall, West Campus collaborated with Tesla Start, a program made for students looking to start a career in Tesla as a field technician. If passed, students will have a guaranteed position as a Field Technician as long as they accept within 30-days of completion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/tesla/|title=Tesla START {{!}} Miami Dade College|website=www.mdc.edu|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/article238045574.html|title=MDC celebrates first graduating class at its new Tesla center|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Carrie P. Meek Entrepreneurial Educational Center ===\nThe Carrie P. Meek Entrepreneurial Educational Center is an outreach center founded in 1989. It is named after the first African-American women in the Florida senate, the [[Carrie P. Meek]]. The Carrie Meek Foundation Scholarship Program supports the MDC Entrepreneurial Educational Center campus based in [[Liberty City (Miami)|liberty city]], Miami. This is an institution based on offering young people the best possible education, mainly to impoverished neighborhoods. This campus offers college credit courses but focuses on non-credit courses and vocational programs, seminars, and workshops to train people for employment.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mdc.edu/north/campus-information/eec.aspx |title=Carrie P. Meek Entrepreneurial Education Center|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Academics ==\nOut of approximately 165,000 students, on average, almost 6,000 go on to earn a bachelor's degree, associate degrees, vocational, technical, or college credit certificates. Associate in Arts transfer students from Miami Dade College go on to transfer primarily to schools within the [[State University System of Florida]]. Although, some do transfer to out-of-state institutions, mainly through articulation agreements made between institutions. As a student in Miami Dade College, you are able to pursue an Associate or bachelor's degrees in over 70 majors with the option of also taking part in non-credit credit courses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mdc.edu/mdcglobal/ci/academic-services/noncredit-courses.aspx|title=Miami Dade College {{!}} Confucius Institute|website=www.mdc.edu|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> Students also have the opportunity to enroll in the honors program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://study.com/articles/Miami_Dade_College_in_Miami_FL.html|title=Miami Dade College: Academics, Admissions & Tuition Info|website=Study.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref>\n\nAlthough students are offered a wide variety of majors, there are currently a list of top three majors in Miami Dade College which include Liberal Arts, Humanities, Nursing, and Business.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.niche.com/colleges/miami-dade-college/majors/|title=Miami Dade College Majors|website=Niche|language=en|access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref> Allied Health Professions and Computer Information Systems follow these majors, naming them in the top five majors chosen by students.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.collegefactual.com/colleges/miami-dade-college/academic-life/|title=Miami Dade College Academics|date=2013-02-20|website=College Factual|language=en|access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Miami Dade College's Schools of Engineering and Technology that develops students to researchers, used a million-plus U.S dollars grant from the [[National Science Foundation]] to start a computer laboratory used by students so they can apply their skills in resolving real-life-problems.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Miami Dade College Program Develops Students into Researchers\" by Schroen, Anna - Diverse Issues in Higher Education, Vol. 30, Issue 13, August 1, 2013 {{!}} Online Research Library: Questia |url=https://www.questia.com/magazine/1G1-339728552/miami-dade-college-program-develops-students-into |website=www.questia.com |accessdate=February 24, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://eds.a.ebscohost.com/ehost/detail/detail?vid=12&sid=22328fd5-65d1-4887-8e4d-de62af6ee01b@sdc-v-sessmgr06&bdata=JnNpdGU9ZWhvc3QtbGl2ZQ==|title=Miami Dade College Program Develops Students into Researchers.|last=Schroen|first=Anna|date=August 1, 2013|website=ebscohost.com|access-date=2019-02-07|url-access=registration}}</ref>\n\nIn fall of 2019, the college implemented the Tesla START program for the purpose of teaching students how to become electric vehicle technicians.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/education/article237969394.html|title=MDC students are being trained to fix cars of the future. Here's how Tesla is involved|last=Marchante|first=Michelle|date=December 4, 2019|work=Miami Herald|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn the Fall semester of 2019, Miami Dade College implemented a learning degree for students to gain a College Credit or Associate in Science in [[Cybersecurity Information Sharing Act|Cybersecurity.]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.floridatrend.com/article/27744/miami-dade-college-combats-critical-shortage-in-cybersecurity|title=Miami Dade College Combats Critical Shortage in Cybersecurity|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe Inside Out Prison Exchange Program that MDC offers, intends to bring college students together and inmates for a semester-long learning at [[Everglades Correctional Institution]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/education/article234185042.html|title=Miami Dade College is hosting classes behind bars. Inmates get the best grades.|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Tuition and Fees<ref name=\"nces.ed.gov\">{{Cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/collegenavigator/|title=College Navigator - National Center for Education Statistics|website=nces.ed.gov|access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref>\n!\n!2015/2016\n!2016/2017\n!2017/2018\n!2018/2019\n|-\n|In-State\n|$2,838\n|$2,838\n|$2,838\n|$2,838\n|-\n|Out-of-State\n|$9,661\n|$9,661\n|$9,661\n|$9,661\n|-\n|Books and Supplies\n|$1,500\n|$1,600\n|$1,600\n|$1,500\n|}\n\nIn the graduation year of 2016 in Miami Dade College, 13,351 degrees were awarded between undergraduate and graduate programs with majority of the recipients being Hispanic. The degrees were awarded to 59.9% of women while they were awarded to a percentage of 40.1% of men.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://datausa.io/profile/university/miami-dade-college/|title=Miami Dade College {{!}} Data USA|website=datausa.io|language=|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref>\n\n'''Tuition and Fees by College Credit Program'''. $118.22 per credit hour for Resident Students, and $402.51 per credit hour for Non-Resident Students. Total Tuition per term (12 credits): $1,558.68 for Resident Students and $6,431.64 for Non-Resident Students. For completed an AA degree is with a total 60 credit that is an estimated around $7,093.02 for Resident Student and $24,156.06 for Non-Resident Student.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mdc.edu/about/tuition.aspx|title=Tuition and Fees {{!}} Miami Dade College|website=www.mdc.edu|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref>\n\n===Enrollment===\n{| style=\"text-align:center; float:right; font-size:85%; margin-left:2em; margin:10px\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ ''Demographics of student body (2017)''<ref>https://www.mdc.edu/ir/Fact%20Book/FB_Credit_Student_Enrollment_Profile.pdf</ref>\n! !! Students !! Florida !! U.S. Census\n|-\n! [[African American]]\n| 16.4% || 16.9% || 13.4%\n|-\n! [[Asian American]]\n| 1.2% || 2.9% || 5.8%\n|-\n! [[European American]]\n| 6.6% || 54.1% || 60.7%\n|-\n! [[Hispanics in the United States|Hispanic American]]\n| 72.1% || 25.6% || 18.1%\n|-\n! [[Multiracial Americans|Multiracial American]]\n| 0.6% || 2.1% || 2.7%\n|-\n! [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]]\n| 0.1% || 0.5% || 1.3%\n|-\n! [[International student]]\n| 2.1% || N/A || N/A\n|}\n\n* [[School for Advanced Studies]] (SAS): A limited admission opportunity for [[Miami-Dade Public Schools|Miami-Dade Public School]] students. High school classes are held at Kendall, Hialeah, Wolfson, and North Campus alongside regular college credit courses, and students choose three college classes per semester to take in place of traditional high school electives. College books and tuition are paid for by the county, and there is no cost to students. Bus service is also provided throughout the county to the schools. The goal is to allow students to earn their [[Associate in Arts]] and [[Associate in Science]] degree while earning their high school diploma. SAS is the 15th best high school in the nation, and is repeatedly one of the highest ranking high schools.<ref>[http://www.newsweek.com/id/201160/?s=school+for+advanced+studies&q=2009/rank/1 America's Top Public High Schools - Newsweek]</ref> MDC also has a virtual college, where a degree can be attained completely over the internet.\n* [[Dual enrollment|Dual Enrollment]]: The college offers Dual Enrollment for students who currently are attending Miami-Dade County public high school, private high schools,  or home school. Dual enrollment allows students to enroll in a college course. The credits that are gained will be used toward both high school graduation and are accepted toward an Associate or bachelor's degree at Miami Date college.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/future-students/high-school/dual-enrollment.aspx|title=Miami Dade Academics|last=|first=|date=|website=mdc.edu|access-date=}}</ref>\n*Miami Dade Honors College: Beginning in May 2019, Miami Dade College decided to team up with the [https://welcome.miami.edu/ University of Miami] to provide more enrollment opportunities for student. They now have a 10-year agreement, \"This partnership ensures MDC students continue to have access to quality and affordable higher education,\" <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Padr\u00f3n|first=Eduardo J.|last2=Levitt|first2=Theodore|date=September 1999|title=Miami-Dade Community College: Forging New Urban Partnerships|journal=New Directions for Community Colleges|volume=1999|issue=107|pages=15\u201322|doi=10.1002/cc.10702|issn=0194-3081}}</ref> said MDC's Executive VP and Provost Dr. Lenore Rodicio. This agreement will guarantee Miami Dade Honors College students acceptance and merit-based financial support at the University of Miami if they meet transfer requirements. This 10-year agreement will run until May 31, 2028. The enrollment for the fall semester will be limited to 300 MDC students. The enrollment for the spring semester will be limited to 150 MDC transfers.\n\n=== Total Enrollment (all undergraduate) ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Undergraduate Enrollment<ref name=\"nces.ed.gov\"/>\n!Undergraduate Student Age\n!Percentage\n!Undergraduate Student Residence\n!Percentage\n|-\n|24 and Under\n|72%\n|In-State\n|98%\n|-\n|25 and Older\n|28%\n|Out-of-State\n|1%\n|-\n|Age Unknown\n|0%\n|Foreign Countries\n|1%\n|}\n\n=== Financial Aid ===\nMDC offers many scholarships and financial aid. Under the financial aid we have Pell Grants, Student Loans.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mdc.edu/financialaid/how-aid-works/grants.aspx|title=Grants {{!}} Financial Aid {{!}} Miami Dade College|website=www.mdc.edu|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> The average reported annual net price for Miami Dade College for students receiving grants or scholarship aid was $7,062 in 2017/2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.collegesimply.com/colleges/florida/miami-dade-college/price/|title=Miami Dade College - Net Price, Tuition, Cost to Attend, Financial Aid and Student Loans|last=CollegeSimply|website=CollegeSimply|language=en|access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref> \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Financial Aid\n!Type of Aid\n!Avg./ Student\n!Student Receiving\n|-\n|Annual Total Grant Aid\n|$5,174\n|81%\n|-\n|Pell Grant\n|$4,917\n|69%\n|-\n|Federal Student Loan\n|$5,750\n|3%\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Grants ''2017-2018''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/collegenavigator/?q=miami+dade+college&s=all&id=135717#finaid|title=College grant navigator|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unigo.com/scholarships/by-college/miami-dade-college-scholarships|title=Miami Dade scholarships|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n!Grant Type\n!Amount of Aid Given\n|-\n|Federal Grants\n|$36,660,504\n|-\n|Pell Grants\n|$131,992,187\n|-\n|Institutional Grants\n|$4,233,250\n|-\n|State/Local Grants\n|$1,415,779\n|}\n\n==Athletics==\nMiami Dade College competes in five sports, men's basketball, men's baseball, women's basketball, women's softball, and women's volleyball. In total, they have 85 student athletes made up of 38 men and 47 women.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.collegefactual.com/colleges/miami-dade-college/student-life/sports/|title=Miami Dade College Sports|date=2013-02-20|website=College Factual|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref>\n\nMiami Dade's Baseball team program started in 1962. Although at the time, Kendall campus, North campus, and Wolfson campus had their own individual fielded teams. However, once the school changed to a four-year college from a community college, they united to make a baseball team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.baseball-almanac.com/college/miami_dade_college_baseball_players.shtml|title=Miami Dade College Baseball Players Who Made it to a Major League Baseball Team|website=www.baseball-almanac.com|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref>\n\nMiami Dade college's athletic teams have won 35 NJCAA national titles, 15 in women's sports.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://news.mdc.edu/press_release/miami-dade-college-lady-sharks-win-the-2019-fcsaa-state-volleyball-tournament-headed-to-nationals/ |title=Miami Dade College Lady Sharks Win the 2019 FCSAA State Volleyball Tournament, Headed to Nationals! |website=MDC News |language=en-US |access-date=2019-12-04}}</ref>\n\nThe school's athletic teams competed in the [[Southern Conference (NJCAA)|Southern Conference]] of the [[Florida State College Activities Association]], a body of the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] [[NJCAA Region 8|Region 8]]. Due to their players and good ranking, Miami Dade College was a \"can't miss stop\" for MLB scouts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/sports/college/state-college-sports/article225029880.html|title='Can't miss stop' for MLB scouts, Miami Dade College baseball continues to shine|website=miamiherald|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref>\n\n== Arts and culture ==\n[[File:Hialeah Campus Stairway Art.jpg|alt=|thumb|Stairs leading to the far side of the Main building in the Hialeah Campus|left|229x229px]]\n[[File:Stairway Mural.jpg|thumb|Outside Stair mural connections of the three floors of the Main building in the Hialeah Campus |alt=|516x516px]]\nMiami Dade College has been collecting art at its individual campuses since the 1960s. Over the years, the collection has grown to more than 1,600 works in all mediums and genres, including painting, sculpture, works on paper, photography, video, film, installation and public sculpture.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.miamiartguide.com/the-influencers-i-ii-prominent-works-from-the-mdc-permanent-art-collection/|title=The Influencers I & II: Prominent Works from the MDC Permanent Art Collection {{!}} Miami Art Guide|website=www.miamiartguide.com|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> MDC Hialeah Campus opened an [[Art]] Gallery in late 2018 in Hialeah, Florida.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hialeah Gallery - Hialeah Campus {{!}} Miami Dade College |url=http://www.mdc.edu/hialeah/gallery/default.aspx |website=mdc.edu |accessdate=17 October 2018 }}</ref> MDC Hialeah Campus Arts & Cultural Programs are partially supported by [[John S. and James L. Knight Foundation|The John S. and James L. Knight Foundation.]]\n\n[[File:Modern David MDC NORTH.jpg|thumb|191x191px|Modern Depiction of David by dEmo Missoni located at MDC North Campus|alt=|left]]\n\nThe college has an \"Emerging Artist Annual Exhibition\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/galleries/programs/emerging.aspx|title=Miami Dade College Galleries of Art + Design|website=www.mdc.edu|access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref> which allows student to display their art in the \"Art + Design\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/galleries/|title=Miami Dade College Galleries of Art + Design|website=www.mdc.edu|access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.miaminewtimes.com/arts/mdc-museum-of-art-design-reopens-with-by-the-people-and-this-situation-10234783|title=MDC's Museum of Art + Design Reopens With Two Shows After Renovation|last=Vazquez|first=Neil|date=2018-04-06|website=Miami New Times|access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.artnews.com/2016/02/22/jeremy-mikolajczak-named-ceo-of-tucson-museum-of-art/|title=Jeremy Mikolajczak Named CEO of Tucson Museum of Art|last=Ghorashi|first=Hannah|date=2016-02-22|website=ARTnews|access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref> museum. Miami Dade College also has an \"MDC live Art\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.miaminewtimes.com/arts/the-best-things-to-do-in-miami-september-27-to-october-3-10764423|title=The Best Things to Do in Miami This Week|last=Tracy|first=Jesse Scott, Liz|date=2018-09-26|website=Miami New Times|access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.miaminewtimes.com/arts/things-to-do-miami-arts-and-cultural-events-2018-2019-10787408|title=The Best Arts Events of Miami's 2018-19 Season|last=Scott|first=Emily Bloch, Jesse|date=2018-10-03|website=Miami New Times|access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref> event which allows student to perform on stage and inspire others through their performance of art; both are open to the community.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/miami/article/Museum-of-Art-and-Design-at-MDC-Presents-The-Speculative-Machine-Series-of-Public-Programs-20190128|title=Museum of Art and Design at MDC Presents The Speculative Machine Series of Public Programs|last=Desk|first=BWW News|website=BroadwayWorld.com|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/miami/article/Museum-of-Art-and-Design-at-MDC-Presents-The-Speculative-Machine-Series-of-Public-Programs-20190128|title=Museum of Art and Design at MDC Presents The Speculative Machine Series of Public Programs|last=Desk|first=BWW News|website=BroadwayWorld.com|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref> As a matter of fact, MDC North campus is home home to a prestigious collection of sculptures produced by renowned artists such as Alfredo Halegna, [[Rafael Consuegra]], [[William King (artist)|William King]] and Mario Felipe Almaguer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.linccweb.org/webscripts/lwauth.aspx?calling_system=ezproxy&institute=flcc1600&url=http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=a9h&AN=24329601&site=ehost-live|title=around campus|last=|first=|date=|website=www.linccweb.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref>\n\nAnnually since 1964, Miami Dade College has awarded the Francis Wolfson Art Scholarship. More than 200 students from Miami Dade College and its outreach center, the New School of the Arts, have received this scholarship. The winners in 2018 each received $1,500.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/education/article209165064.html|title=Five at Miami Dade College win 2018 Frances Wolfson Art Scholarships|website=miamiherald|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mdcfoundation.com/donor-relations/donor-stories/donor-news-frances-wolfson?|title=Donor News Frances Wolfson|website=www.mdcfoundation.com|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref>\n\n== Notable alumni ==\n{{main|List of Miami Dade College alumni}}<gallery>\nFile:Ileana Ros-Lehtinen official photo.jpg|[[Ileana Ros-Lehtinen]] Former U.S. Representative\nFile:20080507 Manny Diaz (1).jpg|Manuel \"Manny\" Alberto Diaz<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uscis.gov/archive/archive-citizenship/archived-outstanding-americans-choice/2007-outstanding-american-choice-recipients|title=2007 Outstanding American by Choice Recipients|date=2011-08-22|website=USCIS|language=en|access-date=2019-12-12}}</ref> [[Manny Diaz (Florida politician)|Mayor of Miami 2001-2009]]\nFile:Dr. Elsa Murano - Texas A&M.JPG|[[Elsa Murano]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hsf.net/stories-detail?storyId=101721754|title=HSF: HSF Stories Detail|last=|first=|date=|website=www.hsf.net|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-13}}</ref> [[List of Texas A&M University presidents|President of Texas A&M University]]\nFile:Mireya Moscoso in 2012.jpg|[[Mireya Moscoso]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.councilwomenworldleaders.org/mireya-moscoso.html|title=Mireya Moscoso|website=Council of Women World Leaders|language=en|access-date=2019-12-13}}</ref> [[List of heads of state of Panama|President of Panama]] from 1999 to 2004. First female President\nFile:John L. Mica 113th Congress.jpg|[[John Mica]]\nFile:Flickr - nicogenin - 66\u00e8me Festival de Venise (Mostra) - Sylvester Stallone (26).jpg|[[Sylvester Stallone]] American Actor\nFile:StevenBauer08.jpg|[[Steven Bauer]] American-Cuban Actor\nFile:Glenn Howerton (9365867002).jpg|[[Glenn Howerton]] American Actor\nFile:Oscar Isaac by Gage Skidmore.jpg|[[Oscar Isaac]] American Actor and SInger\nFile:Ra\u00fal Iba\u00f1ez on September 9, 2012.jpg|[[Ra\u00fal Iba\u00f1ez|Raul Ibanez]] Professional American Baseball Player\nFile:Mike Piazza answers a question during the HOF news conference.jpg|[[Mike Piazza]] Former American Professional Baseball Player\nFile:Steve Carlton 1995.jpg|[[Steve Carlton]] Former American Professional Baseball Player\nFile:Polanco-crop.jpg|[[Pl\u00e1cido Polanco]] American-Dominican professional baseball player\nFile:2013 Imagen Foundation Awards, Natalie Martinez.jpg|[[Natalie Martinez]] American Actress and Model\nFile:Harry Wayne Casey 2017.jpg|[[Harry Wayne Casey|Harry Wayne Case]]y American Musician          \n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.mdc.edu/}}\n\n{{Greater Miami}}\n{{Florida College System}}\n{{Florida College Sports}}\n\n{{Coord|25|46|40|N|80|11|26|W|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1959 establishments in Florida]]\n[[Category:Air traffic controller schools]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1959]]\n[[Category:Florida College System]]\n[[Category:Miami Dade College| ]]\n[[Category:North American Soccer League (1968\u20131984) stadiums]]\n[[Category:Public universities and colleges in Florida]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges accredited by the Southern Association of Colleges and Schools]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Miami-Dade County, Florida]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox university\n| name = Miami Dade College\n| former_names = Dade Junior College<br />Miami Dade Junior College<br />Miami Dade Community College\n| other_name = Dade\n| image = Miami Dade College logo.svg\n| established = {{start date and age|1959}}\n| type = [[Public College]]\n| endowment = $491.7 million (2019)<ref>As of June 30, 2019. {{cite web |url=https://www.nacubo.org/-/media/Nacubo/Documents/EndowmentFiles/2019-NTSE-Endowment-Market-Values--FINAL-January-30-2020.ashx|title=U.S. and Canadian Institutions Listed by Fiscal Year (FY) 2019 Endowment Market Value and Change in Endowment Market Value from FY 2018 to FY 2019 |publisher=National Association of College and University Business Officers and TIAA |access-date=February 28, 2020}}</ref>\n| president = Rolando Montoya (interim)\n| city = [[Miami]]\n| state = [[Florida]]\n| country = United States\n| campus = Urban\n| students = 165,000 (2014\u201315)\n| faculty = 6,500<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/main/about/facts_in_brief.asp|title=Page Not Found - Miami Dade College|work=mdc.edu|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n| colors = Blue & Gray {{color box|#0033a0}} {{color box|#737b82}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/mktg/logos.html|title=MDC Logo Guidelines|publisher=Miami Dade College|accessdate=March 10, 2016}}</ref>\n| mascot = Finn the Shark<ref>[https://news.mdc.edu/finn-wins Finn Wins!]</ref>\n| website = [http://www.mdc.edu/ www.mdc.edu]|\n}}\n\n'''Miami Dade College''' ('''Miami Dade,''' '''MDC''' or '''Dade''')<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/30/us/30dade.html|title=Eduardo J. Padr\u00f3n, the college's president since 1995.|last=|first=|date=|work=A Community College in Florida Works to Attract the Poor and the Presidential|access-date=}}</ref> is a [[public college]] in [[Miami]], [[Florida]]. Founded in 1959, it has a total of eight [[campus]]es and twenty-one [[outreach]] centers throughout [[Miami-Dade County]]. It is the largest college in the Florida College System with over 165,000 students <ref>{{cite web |title=Miami-Dade College (U.S) |url=https://fotw.info/flags/us_u_mmd.html |website=FOTW \"Flags of the world\" |accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Padr\u00f3n|first=Eduardo J.|date=June 2013|title=Increasing the Relevance of Curricular and Student Services in the Urban Community College|journal=New Directions for Community Colleges |volume=2013 |issue=162 |pages=63\u201373 |doi=10.1002/cc.20060 |issn=0194-3081}}</ref> and the second-largest college or university in the United States. Miami Dade College enrolls a significantly larger amount of Hispanic students each year compared to other colleges and universities in the state of Florida.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/programs/digest/d17/tables/dt17_312.40.asp|title=Digest of Education Statistics, 2017|website=nces.ed.gov|language=EN|access-date=2019-12-04}}</ref> Miami Dade College has 8 different campuses that make up the college and the first being the North Campus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.miamitodaynews.com/2019/11/12/rolando-montoya-interim-college-president-sees-tech-courses-demand-soar/|title=Rolando Montoya: Interim college president sees tech courses demand soar|date=2019-11-12|website=Miami Today|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-04}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\nInitially established on the farm of a county high school, Dade County Junior College\u2014as it was formerly known\u2014had its modest beginnings. Like most organizations at the time, it was a segregated institution. It wasn't until 1962 that [[Desegregation in the United States|desegregation]] took full effect; black and white students could share full schedules together. In 1963, the first new building was constructed, and Peter Masiko would become president for the next 18 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.linccweb.org/webscripts/lwauth.aspx?calling_system=ezproxy&institute=flcc1600&url=https://infoweb.newsbank.com/apps/news/document-view?p=AWNB&t=&sort=YMD_date:A&fld-base-0=alltext&maxresults=20&val-base-0=%20%22Dade%20County%20Junior%20College%22&docref=news/0EB360A06EE6EE4D|title=LINCCWeb Catalog Search|website=www.linccweb.org|access-date=2020-02-18}}</ref> As the years progressed, more campuses began opening across the county: the Kendall Campus and Wolfson Campus.\n\nInitially, the college had an open admissions policy, meaning anyone who could afford to pay was allowed to study at the campus. Due to this, the college aimed to improve its academic stance among alumni. To encourage this movement, a Medical Center was built for students in [[Allied health professions|Allied Health]] and Nursing ([[Registered nurse|RN]]) programs. As the number of Cuban exiles and refugees began to rise in 1980, and [[Outreach|outreach center]] was built in the city of [[Hialeah]]. This allowed refugees and immigrants educational opportunities that they wouldn't be able to achieve otherwise. Another outreach center, the InterAmerican center, was built to accommodate [[bilingual education]]. The Homestead Campus was built in 1990 in [[Homestead, Florida|Homestead]] to relieve the concerns of students having to drive to the Kendall Campus In Miami. In the mid-1990s, the college began to rely heavily on the Miami Dade College Foundation as the [[Florida Legislature|Florida legislature]] reduced the state's education budget. The college also had to figure out new ways of recruiting students and it began its \"Successful Alumni\" campaign in the late 1990s, marketing the success of the college's alumni to local prospective students.\n\nBeginning in 2001, the college implemented a strategic plan to revamp the college and its recruiting goals. In 2002, the college disbanded its [[Honors colleges and programs|Honors Program]] and created The Honors College for talented high school graduates.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mdc.edu/about/history.aspx|title=History of MDC {{!}} Miami Dade College|website=www.mdc.edu|access-date=2020-02-05}}</ref> The [[Honors colleges and programs|Honors College]] is a representation of Miami Dade College's most [[Academically gifted|academically-gifted]] students in different fields and was originally based on the three larger campuses (Wolfson, Kendall, and North).In 2006, Miami Dade College surpassed 1.5 million students enrolled throughout its history. In 2007, The Honors College expanded into the InterAmerican Campus with The Honors College Dual Language Honors Program to tailor to the needs of the growing Spanish-speaking population in the [[United States]] as well as abroad. The Dual Language Honors Program opened its doors to bilingual students who wish to continue their careers with professional fluency in the English and Spanish languages. In 2009, The MDC Honors College Dual Language Program earned the merit of Innovation of the Year in the Learning and Teaching Department from the League for Innovation. In 2018, Miami Dade was awarded and recognized for its path to economic and social mobility by the Aspen Institute. The award received was the $1 million Aspen Prize.\n\nOn February 1, 2019, [[Eduardo J. Padr\u00f3n|Eduardo Padron]], Miami Dade College President, announced that he plans to retire from the position he has held since 1995.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Campus\n! Year opened\n! Students\n! Size\n! Location\n|-\n| Carrie P. Meek Entrepreneurial Education Center<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/north/campus-information/eec.aspx|title=Carrie P. Meek Entrepreneurial Education Center - North Campus - Miami Dade College|work=mdc.edu|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n| 1989\n| 2,500+\n| NA\n| [[Liberty City (Miami)|Liberty City]]\n|-\n| Hialeah Campus<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/hialeah/|title=Miami Dade College - Hialeah Campus|work=mdc.edu|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n| 1980<br />2005 (Official designation)\n| NA\n| 8 acres\n| [[Hialeah, Florida|Hialeah]]\n|-\n| Homestead Campus<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/homestead/|title=Homestead Campus|work=mdc.edu|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n| 1990\n| \n| 18 acres\n| [[Homestead, Florida|Downtown Homestead]]\n|-\n| Eduardo J. Padron Campus<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/padron/|title=Padron Campus Campus|work=mdc.edu|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n| 1986<br />2001 (Official designation)\n| 6,500\n| 4 acres\n| [[Little Havana]], Miami\n|-\n| Kendall Campus<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/kendall/|title=Kendall Campus|work=mdc.edu|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n| 1967\n| 66,500\n| 185 acres\n| [[Kendall, Florida|Kendall]], Miami\n|-\n| MDC-West<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/west/|title=MDC West - Miami Dade College|work=mdc.edu|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n| 2005\n| NA\n| 10 acres\n| [[Doral, Florida|Doral]]\n|-\n| Medical Campus<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/medical/|title=Medical Campus|work=mdc.edu|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n| 1977\n| NA\n| 4.3 acres\n|  (Miami)|[[Allapattah]], Miami\n|-\n| North Campus<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/north/about.asp|title=About North Campus - Miami-Dade College - North Campus|work=mdc.edu|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n| 1960\n| 41,000\n| 245 acres\n| [[Westview, Florida|Westview]]\n|-\n| '''[[Wolfson Campus]]<br />(Main campus)'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/wolfson/campus-information/default.aspx|title=Campus Information - Wolfson Campus - Miami Dade College|work=mdc.edu|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n| '''1970'''\n| '''27,000'''\n| '''15 acres'''\n| '''[[Downtown Miami]]'''\n|-\n|}\nMiami Dade College has seven campuses and two centers, with its main campus being the Wolfson Campus in downtown [[Miami]].These eight campuses and various outreach centers are located throughout [[Miami-Dade County, Florida|Miami-Dade County]]. The Honors College is currently represented on four campuses, with a new [[Multilingualism|bilingual]] program (English-Spanish) at the Padron Campus.  All campuses have different schools for various disciplines (engineering, business, etc.). Some campuses also operate [[Dual enrollment|dual-enrollment]] programs for high school students. Most campuses also have College Preparatory or English as a Second Language ([[ESL]]) courses that help students pass the Computerized Placement Test (CPT) that is required for admittance and proves prospective students are qualified to take college-level mathematics and [[English studies|English]] courses\n\n=== North Campus  ===\n[[File:MDC north campush science.jpg|thumb|Miami Dade North Campus Science Complex|alt=|251x251px]]North Campus has specialized programs that train future firefighters, police officers, and Emergency medical service personnels. It also has a School of Entertainment and Design Technology. This campus partners with Florida Agricultural and Mechanical University (FAMU) for engineering programs. The North Campus operates the Carrie Meek Entrepreneurial Education Center in Liberty City. The campus also offers a Bachelor in Applied Science degree in Public Safety that is housed within the School of Justice.\n\n=== Kendall Campus ===\nKendall Campus houses the college's athletic teams. The 185-acre campus opened in 1967.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/kendall/campus-information/default.aspx|title=Campus Information - Kendall Campus {{!}} Miami Dade College|website=www.mdc.edu|access-date=2019-02-08}}</ref> It is home to the Honors College and the Miami Dade College Foundation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/kendall/|title=Miami Dade College Kendall Campus|last=|first=|date=|website=mdc.edu|access-date=}}</ref> Apart from the Latin Jazz experience being held at the Kendall Campus they also allow student to receive community service hours that can be apply to their degree through the CSI and Procedural Justice Camps for the youth, including those with disabilities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/article230780629.html|title=Camps at college mean summertime fun, and, yes, some learning|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>[[File:Kendall Campus - Building R.jpg|thumb|Kendall Campus - Building R|alt=|left|267x267px]]\n\n=== Wolfson Campus ===\nThe Wolfson Campus was opened in 1970 and is the only comprehensive urban campus in the city. Located within the city's financial, governmental, technological and cultural hubs, Wolfson educates over 27,000 students each year. MDC's Wolfson Campus program is designed Accelerate, Retain, Complete with Opportunities and Support and is aimed at creating a support network for 600 STEM students.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/education/article41551710.html|title=Miami Herald|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Each year, this campus hosts the [[Miami Book Fair International]], the nation's largest literary festival.The Miami Culinary Institute of Miami Dade College is located in this campus where it offers a Chefs Apprentice Program, Culinary Arts Management and an Associate in science. It is a multi-million dollar architectural project.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/culinary/programs.aspx|title=Programs {{!}} Miami Culinary Institute {{!}} Miami Dade College|website=www.mdc.edu|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref>\n\nThe goal is to keep Hispanic and other low-income high-need students engaged in the program. The campus has two art galleries, a library, and two computer courtyards. The [[Miami Dade College (Wolfson Campus)|Wolfson Campus]] also has business and paralegal studies programs.[[File:Building REVEST Program.jpg|thumb|189x189px|Hialeah Outreach Center, located at 3680 W 16 Ave Hialeah, Fl 33012. House of MDC REVEST Program.|alt=]]\n[[File:Center Pardon Campus.jpg|thumb|251x251px|Center of Flags in the Padr\u00f3n Campus]]\n\n=== Medical Center ===\nMiami Dade College opened its medical campus in 1977.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/medical/campus-information/|title=Campus Information - Medical Campus {{!}} Miami Dade College|website=www.mdc.edu|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref> It is located in Miami's Medical District near downtown Miami, trains students in the Nursing (BSN/RN) and Allied Health fields, completing the Associate in Applied Science and school degree that will allow them immediate entry into health professions. The Medical Campus also offers bachelor's degrees.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/academics/programs/bachelors.aspx|title=Bachelor's Degree Programs {{!}} Academics {{!}} Miami Dade College|website=www.mdc.edu|access-date=2019-02-08}}</ref> The campus shares its complex with The University of Miami's School of Medicine, [[Jackson Memorial Hospital]], Veterans Administration Hospital and Miami Dade College Public Health Service<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/about/campuses.aspx|title=Campuses {{!}} Miami Dade College|website=www.mdc.edu|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref>\n\n=== Homestead Campus ===\nThe Homestead Campus contains the college's aviation program, one of thirteen schools in the nation accredited ATC-CTI (Air Traffic Control Collegiate Training Initiative) status by the [[Federal Aviation Administration]] (FAA). It also possesses, in addition to the Medical Campus, the renowned Benjamin Leon School of Nursing that has trained over fifty percent of nurses in Miami-Dade County.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/nursing/|title=School of Nursing {{!}} Miami Dade College|website=www.mdc.edu|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref>[[File:Picture of the Eduardo J Padron campus.jpg|thumb|Building 6 that is located on the Eduardo J. Padron campus of Miami Dade College, minutes from downtown, Miami. |alt=|left]]\n\n=== Eduardo J. Padr\u00f3n Campus ===\n[[Eduardo J. Padr\u00f3n]] Campus is the sixth campus created by Miami Dade College. It was previously known as the InterAmerican campus, but was later changed to Eduardo J Padr\u00f3n in honor of MDC's president being with the college for 50 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.mdc.edu/press_release/miami-dade-college-to-rename-its-interamerican-campus-the-eduardo-j-padron-campus-on-may-17/|title=Miami Dade College to Rename its InterAmerican Campus the Eduardo J. Padr\u00f3n Campus on May 17|website=MDC News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> This campus was first created in 1972, but didn't get the status of a \"campus\" til March 27, 2001.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mdc.edu/padron/campus-information/|title=Campus Information - Eduardo J. Padr\u00f3n Campus {{!}} Miami Dade College|website=www.mdc.edu|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> This campus contains the School of Education which offers Bachelor of Science (BS) degrees.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/iac/|title=Miami Dade College Inter American Campus|last=|first=|date=|website=mdc. edu|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== New World School of the Arts ===\nThe [[New World School of the Arts]] is both a high school and a college that focuses on visual arts, theatre, dance, and music. Admission requirements include an audition or review of the applicant's art portfolio. Aside from New World School of the Arts and the MEEC, there are nineteen other MDC outreach centers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/main/campus%5Ffinder/outreach%5Fcenters/|title=Outreach Centers|work=mdc.edu|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nwsa.mdc.edu|title=New World School Of The Arts|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Hialeah Campus ==\n[[File:Miami Dade Hialeah.jpg|alt=|thumb|This is a night view of the Hialeah Miami Dade Campus|279x279px]]The [[Hialeah, Florida|Hialeah]] Campus is a former extension of the North Campus, houses a large and comprehensive English language training program for \nspeakers of other languages in various instructional formats. Construction of a 1,000 car parking garage and a new building housing classrooms, science labs, and student services was completed in 2014.The out doors of the campus has palm trees with a sufficient amount of chairs for students waiting on their next class or for eating some food. The inside of the campus may seem small but has four floors on one side of the building and three floors on the other side of the building. The Hialeah Campus offers associate programs and the Bachelor of Applied Science in Supervision and Management.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/hialeah/campus-information/default.aspx|title=Campus Information - Hialeah Campus - Miami Dade College|website=www.mdc.edu|access-date=2019-02-08}}</ref>\n\n=== West Campus ===\nWest Campus opened in March 2006 for students residing in or near Doral.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/west/campus-information/default.aspx|title=Campus Information - MDC West - Miami Dade College|website=www.mdc.edu|access-date=2019-02-08}}</ref> The campus had begun construction on a new 5 story garage in January 2012; in October of the same year, the garage collapsed, this collapse resulted in the death of 4 construction workers. In 2015 the contractors and subcontractors involved in the project reached an agreement with Miami Dade College in the amount of 33.5 million dollars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/community/miami-dade/doral/article20700564.html|title=Miami Dade College wins $33 million settlement over collapsed parking garage|last=Teproff|first=Carli|date=May 11, 2015|website=The Miami Herald|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref> This Fall, West Campus collaborated with Tesla Start, a program made for students looking to start a career in Tesla as a field technician. If passed, students will have a guaranteed position as a Field Technician as long as they accept within 30-days of completion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/tesla/|title=Tesla START {{!}} Miami Dade College|website=www.mdc.edu|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/article238045574.html|title=MDC celebrates first graduating class at its new Tesla center|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Carrie P. Meek Entrepreneurial Educational Center ===\nThe Carrie P. Meek Entrepreneurial Educational Center is an outreach center founded in 1989. It is named after the first African-American women in the Florida senate, the [[Carrie P. Meek]]. The Carrie Meek Foundation Scholarship Program supports the MDC Entrepreneurial Educational Center campus based in [[Liberty City (Miami)|liberty city]], Miami. This is an institution based on offering young people the best possible education, mainly to impoverished neighborhoods. This campus offers college credit courses but focuses on non-credit courses and vocational programs, seminars, and workshops to train people for employment.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mdc.edu/north/campus-information/eec.aspx |title=Carrie P. Meek Entrepreneurial Education Center|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Academics ==\nOut of approximately 165,000 students, on average, almost 6,000 go on to earn a bachelor's degree, associate degrees, vocational, technical, or college credit certificates. Associate in Arts transfer students from Miami Dade College go on to transfer primarily to schools within the [[State University System of Florida]]. Although, some do transfer to out-of-state institutions, mainly through articulation agreements made between institutions. As a student in Miami Dade College, you are able to pursue an Associate or bachelor's degrees in over 70 majors with the option of also taking part in non-credit credit courses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mdc.edu/mdcglobal/ci/academic-services/noncredit-courses.aspx|title=Miami Dade College {{!}} Confucius Institute|website=www.mdc.edu|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> Students also have the opportunity to enroll in the honors program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://study.com/articles/Miami_Dade_College_in_Miami_FL.html|title=Miami Dade College: Academics, Admissions & Tuition Info|website=Study.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref>\n\nAlthough students are offered a wide variety of majors, there are currently a list of top three majors in Miami Dade College which include Liberal Arts, Humanities, Nursing, and Business.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.niche.com/colleges/miami-dade-college/majors/|title=Miami Dade College Majors|website=Niche|language=en|access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref> Allied Health Professions and Computer Information Systems follow these majors, naming them in the top five majors chosen by students.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.collegefactual.com/colleges/miami-dade-college/academic-life/|title=Miami Dade College Academics|date=2013-02-20|website=College Factual|language=en|access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Miami Dade College's Schools of Engineering and Technology that develops students to researchers, used a million-plus U.S dollars grant from the [[National Science Foundation]] to start a computer laboratory used by students so they can apply their skills in resolving real-life-problems.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Miami Dade College Program Develops Students into Researchers\" by Schroen, Anna - Diverse Issues in Higher Education, Vol. 30, Issue 13, August 1, 2013 {{!}} Online Research Library: Questia |url=https://www.questia.com/magazine/1G1-339728552/miami-dade-college-program-develops-students-into |website=www.questia.com |accessdate=February 24, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://eds.a.ebscohost.com/ehost/detail/detail?vid=12&sid=22328fd5-65d1-4887-8e4d-de62af6ee01b@sdc-v-sessmgr06&bdata=JnNpdGU9ZWhvc3QtbGl2ZQ==|title=Miami Dade College Program Develops Students into Researchers.|last=Schroen|first=Anna|date=August 1, 2013|website=ebscohost.com|access-date=2019-02-07|url-access=registration}}</ref>\n\nIn fall of 2019, the college implemented the Tesla START program for the purpose of teaching students how to become electric vehicle technicians.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/education/article237969394.html|title=MDC students are being trained to fix cars of the future. Here's how Tesla is involved|last=Marchante|first=Michelle|date=December 4, 2019|work=Miami Herald|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn the Fall semester of 2019, Miami Dade College implemented a learning degree for students to gain a College Credit or Associate in Science in [[Cybersecurity Information Sharing Act|Cybersecurity.]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.floridatrend.com/article/27744/miami-dade-college-combats-critical-shortage-in-cybersecurity|title=Miami Dade College Combats Critical Shortage in Cybersecurity|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe Inside Out Prison Exchange Program that MDC offers, intends to bring college students together and inmates for a semester-long learning at [[Everglades Correctional Institution]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/education/article234185042.html|title=Miami Dade College is hosting classes behind bars. Inmates get the best grades.|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Tuition and Fees<ref name=\"nces.ed.gov\">{{Cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/collegenavigator/|title=College Navigator - National Center for Education Statistics|website=nces.ed.gov|access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref>\n!\n!2015/2016\n!2016/2017\n!2017/2018\n!2018/2019\n|-\n|In-State\n|$2,838\n|$2,838\n|$2,838\n|$2,838\n|-\n|Out-of-State\n|$9,661\n|$9,661\n|$9,661\n|$9,661\n|-\n|Books and Supplies\n|$1,500\n|$1,600\n|$1,600\n|$1,500\n|}\n\nIn the graduation year of 2016 in Miami Dade College, 13,351 degrees were awarded between undergraduate and graduate programs with majority of the recipients being Hispanic. The degrees were awarded to 59.9% of women while they were awarded to a percentage of 40.1% of men.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://datausa.io/profile/university/miami-dade-college/|title=Miami Dade College {{!}} Data USA|website=datausa.io|language=|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref>\n\n'''Tuition and Fees by College Credit Program'''. $118.22 per credit hour for Resident Students, and $402.51 per credit hour for Non-Resident Students. Total Tuition per term (12 credits): $1,558.68 for Resident Students and $6,431.64 for Non-Resident Students. For completed an AA degree is with a total 60 credit that is an estimated around $7,093.02 for Resident Student and $24,156.06 for Non-Resident Student.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mdc.edu/about/tuition.aspx|title=Tuition and Fees {{!}} Miami Dade College|website=www.mdc.edu|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref>\n\n===Enrollment===\n{| style=\"text-align:center; float:right; font-size:85%; margin-left:2em; margin:10px\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ ''Demographics of student body (2017)''<ref>https://www.mdc.edu/ir/Fact%20Book/FB_Credit_Student_Enrollment_Profile.pdf</ref>\n! !! Students !! Florida !! U.S. Census\n|-\n! [[African American]]\n| 16.4% || 16.9% || 13.4%\n|-\n! [[Asian American]]\n| 1.2% || 2.9% || 5.8%\n|-\n! [[European American]]\n| 6.6% || 54.1% || 60.7%\n|-\n! [[Hispanics in the United States|Hispanic American]]\n| 72.1% || 25.6% || 18.1%\n|-\n! [[Multiracial Americans|Multiracial American]]\n| 0.6% || 2.1% || 2.7%\n|-\n! [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]]\n| 0.1% || 0.5% || 1.3%\n|-\n! [[International student]]\n| 2.1% || N/A || N/A\n|}\n\n* [[School for Advanced Studies]] (SAS): A limited admission opportunity for [[Miami-Dade Public Schools|Miami-Dade Public School]] students. High school classes are held at Kendall, Hialeah, Wolfson, and North Campus alongside regular college credit courses, and students choose three college classes per semester to take in place of traditional high school electives. College books and tuition are paid for by the county, and there is no cost to students. Bus service is also provided throughout the county to the schools. The goal is to allow students to earn their [[Associate in Arts]] and [[Associate in Science]] degree while earning their high school diploma. SAS is the 15th best high school in the nation, and is repeatedly one of the highest ranking high schools.<ref>[http://www.newsweek.com/id/201160/?s=school+for+advanced+studies&q=2009/rank/1 America's Top Public High Schools - Newsweek]</ref> MDC also has a virtual college, where a degree can be attained completely over the internet.\n* [[Dual enrollment|Dual Enrollment]]: The college offers Dual Enrollment for students who currently are attending Miami-Dade County public high school, private high schools,  or home school. Dual enrollment allows students to enroll in a college course. The credits that are gained will be used toward both high school graduation and are accepted toward an Associate or bachelor's degree at Miami Date college.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/future-students/high-school/dual-enrollment.aspx|title=Miami Dade Academics|last=|first=|date=|website=mdc.edu|access-date=}}</ref>\n*Miami Dade Honors College: Beginning in May 2019, Miami Dade College decided to team up with the [https://welcome.miami.edu/ University of Miami] to provide more enrollment opportunities for student. They now have a 10-year agreement, \"This partnership ensures MDC students continue to have access to quality and affordable higher education,\" <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Padr\u00f3n|first=Eduardo J.|last2=Levitt|first2=Theodore|date=September 1999|title=Miami-Dade Community College: Forging New Urban Partnerships|journal=New Directions for Community Colleges|volume=1999|issue=107|pages=15\u201322|doi=10.1002/cc.10702|issn=0194-3081}}</ref> said MDC's Executive VP and Provost Dr. Lenore Rodicio. This agreement will guarantee Miami Dade Honors College students acceptance and merit-based financial support at the University of Miami if they meet transfer requirements. This 10-year agreement will run until May 31, 2028. The enrollment for the fall semester will be limited to 300 MDC students. The enrollment for the spring semester will be limited to 150 MDC transfers.\n\n=== Total Enrollment (all undergraduate) ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Undergraduate Enrollment<ref name=\"nces.ed.gov\"/>\n!Undergraduate Student Age\n!Percentage\n!Undergraduate Student Residence\n!Percentage\n|-\n|24 and Under\n|72%\n|In-State\n|98%\n|-\n|25 and Older\n|28%\n|Out-of-State\n|1%\n|-\n|Age Unknown\n|0%\n|Foreign Countries\n|1%\n|}\n\n=== Financial Aid ===\nMDC offers many scholarships and financial aid. Under the financial aid we have Pell Grants, Student Loans.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mdc.edu/financialaid/how-aid-works/grants.aspx|title=Grants {{!}} Financial Aid {{!}} Miami Dade College|website=www.mdc.edu|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> The average reported annual net price for Miami Dade College for students receiving grants or scholarship aid was $7,062 in 2017/2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.collegesimply.com/colleges/florida/miami-dade-college/price/|title=Miami Dade College - Net Price, Tuition, Cost to Attend, Financial Aid and Student Loans|last=CollegeSimply|website=CollegeSimply|language=en|access-date=2019-10-13}}</ref> \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Financial Aid\n!Type of Aid\n!Avg./ Student\n!Student Receiving\n|-\n|Annual Total Grant Aid\n|$5,174\n|81%\n|-\n|Pell Grant\n|$4,917\n|69%\n|-\n|Federal Student Loan\n|$5,750\n|3%\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Grants ''2017-2018''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/collegenavigator/?q=miami+dade+college&s=all&id=135717#finaid|title=College grant navigator|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unigo.com/scholarships/by-college/miami-dade-college-scholarships|title=Miami Dade scholarships|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n!Grant Type\n!Amount of Aid Given\n|-\n|Federal Grants\n|$36,660,504\n|-\n|Pell Grants\n|$131,992,187\n|-\n|Institutional Grants\n|$4,233,250\n|-\n|State/Local Grants\n|$1,415,779\n|}\n\n==Athletics==\nMiami Dade College competes in five sports, men's basketball, men's baseball, women's basketball, women's softball, and women's volleyball. In total, they have 85 student athletes made up of 38 men and 47 women.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.collegefactual.com/colleges/miami-dade-college/student-life/sports/|title=Miami Dade College Sports|date=2013-02-20|website=College Factual|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref>\n\nMiami Dade's Baseball team program started in 1962. Although at the time, Kendall campus, North campus, and Wolfson campus had their own individual fielded teams. However, once the school changed to a four-year college from a community college, they united to make a baseball team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.baseball-almanac.com/college/miami_dade_college_baseball_players.shtml|title=Miami Dade College Baseball Players Who Made it to a Major League Baseball Team|website=www.baseball-almanac.com|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref>\n\nMiami Dade college's athletic teams have won 35 NJCAA national titles, 15 in women's sports.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://news.mdc.edu/press_release/miami-dade-college-lady-sharks-win-the-2019-fcsaa-state-volleyball-tournament-headed-to-nationals/ |title=Miami Dade College Lady Sharks Win the 2019 FCSAA State Volleyball Tournament, Headed to Nationals! |website=MDC News |language=en-US |access-date=2019-12-04}}</ref>\n\nThe school's athletic teams competed in the [[Southern Conference (NJCAA)|Southern Conference]] of the [[Florida State College Activities Association]], a body of the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] [[NJCAA Region 8|Region 8]]. Due to their players and good ranking, Miami Dade College was a \"can't miss stop\" for MLB scouts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/sports/college/state-college-sports/article225029880.html|title='Can't miss stop' for MLB scouts, Miami Dade College baseball continues to shine|website=miamiherald|access-date=2019-02-12}}</ref>\n\n== Arts and culture ==\n[[File:Hialeah Campus Stairway Art.jpg|alt=|thumb|Stairs leading to the far side of the Main building in the Hialeah Campus|left|229x229px]]\n[[File:Stairway Mural.jpg|thumb|Outside Stair mural connections of the three floors of the Main building in the Hialeah Campus |alt=|516x516px]]\nMiami Dade College has been collecting art at its individual campuses since the 1960s. Over the years, the collection has grown to more than 1,600 works in all mediums and genres, including painting, sculpture, works on paper, photography, video, film, installation and public sculpture.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.miamiartguide.com/the-influencers-i-ii-prominent-works-from-the-mdc-permanent-art-collection/|title=The Influencers I & II: Prominent Works from the MDC Permanent Art Collection {{!}} Miami Art Guide|website=www.miamiartguide.com|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> MDC Hialeah Campus opened an [[Art]] Gallery in late 2018 in Hialeah, Florida.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hialeah Gallery - Hialeah Campus {{!}} Miami Dade College |url=http://www.mdc.edu/hialeah/gallery/default.aspx |website=mdc.edu |accessdate=17 October 2018 }}</ref> MDC Hialeah Campus Arts & Cultural Programs are partially supported by [[John S. and James L. Knight Foundation|The John S. and James L. Knight Foundation.]]\n\n[[File:Modern David MDC NORTH.jpg|thumb|191x191px|Modern Depiction of David by dEmo Missoni located at MDC North Campus|alt=|left]]\n\nThe college has an \"Emerging Artist Annual Exhibition\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/galleries/programs/emerging.aspx|title=Miami Dade College Galleries of Art + Design|website=www.mdc.edu|access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref> which allows student to display their art in the \"Art + Design\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mdc.edu/galleries/|title=Miami Dade College Galleries of Art + Design|website=www.mdc.edu|access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.miaminewtimes.com/arts/mdc-museum-of-art-design-reopens-with-by-the-people-and-this-situation-10234783|title=MDC's Museum of Art + Design Reopens With Two Shows After Renovation|last=Vazquez|first=Neil|date=2018-04-06|website=Miami New Times|access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.artnews.com/2016/02/22/jeremy-mikolajczak-named-ceo-of-tucson-museum-of-art/|title=Jeremy Mikolajczak Named CEO of Tucson Museum of Art|last=Ghorashi|first=Hannah|date=2016-02-22|website=ARTnews|access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref> museum. Miami Dade College also has an \"MDC live Art\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.miaminewtimes.com/arts/the-best-things-to-do-in-miami-september-27-to-october-3-10764423|title=The Best Things to Do in Miami This Week|last=Tracy|first=Jesse Scott, Liz|date=2018-09-26|website=Miami New Times|access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.miaminewtimes.com/arts/things-to-do-miami-arts-and-cultural-events-2018-2019-10787408|title=The Best Arts Events of Miami's 2018-19 Season|last=Scott|first=Emily Bloch, Jesse|date=2018-10-03|website=Miami New Times|access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref> event which allows student to perform on stage and inspire others through their performance of art; both are open to the community.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/miami/article/Museum-of-Art-and-Design-at-MDC-Presents-The-Speculative-Machine-Series-of-Public-Programs-20190128|title=Museum of Art and Design at MDC Presents The Speculative Machine Series of Public Programs|last=Desk|first=BWW News|website=BroadwayWorld.com|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/miami/article/Museum-of-Art-and-Design-at-MDC-Presents-The-Speculative-Machine-Series-of-Public-Programs-20190128|title=Museum of Art and Design at MDC Presents The Speculative Machine Series of Public Programs|last=Desk|first=BWW News|website=BroadwayWorld.com|access-date=2019-02-20}}</ref> As a matter of fact, MDC North campus is home home to a prestigious collection of sculptures produced by renowned artists such as Alfredo Halegna, [[Rafael Consuegra]], [[William King (artist)|William King]] and Mario Felipe Almaguer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.linccweb.org/webscripts/lwauth.aspx?calling_system=ezproxy&institute=flcc1600&url=http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=a9h&AN=24329601&site=ehost-live|title=around campus|last=|first=|date=|website=www.linccweb.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref>\n\nAnnually since 1964, Miami Dade College has awarded the Francis Wolfson Art Scholarship. More than 200 students from Miami Dade College and its outreach center, the New School of the Arts, have received this scholarship. The winners in 2018 each received $1,500.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/education/article209165064.html|title=Five at Miami Dade College win 2018 Frances Wolfson Art Scholarships|website=miamiherald|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mdcfoundation.com/donor-relations/donor-stories/donor-news-frances-wolfson?|title=Donor News Frances Wolfson|website=www.mdcfoundation.com|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref>\n\n== Notable alumni ==\n{{main|List of Miami Dade College alumni}}<gallery>\nFile:Ileana Ros-Lehtinen official photo.jpg|[[Ileana Ros-Lehtinen]] Former U.S. Representative\nFile:20080507 Manny Diaz (1).jpg|Manuel \"Manny\" Alberto Diaz<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uscis.gov/archive/archive-citizenship/archived-outstanding-americans-choice/2007-outstanding-american-choice-recipients|title=2007 Outstanding American by Choice Recipients|date=2011-08-22|website=USCIS|language=en|access-date=2019-12-12}}</ref> [[Manny Diaz (Florida politician)|Mayor of Miami 2001-2009]]\nFile:Dr. Elsa Murano - Texas A&M.JPG|[[Elsa Murano]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hsf.net/stories-detail?storyId=101721754|title=HSF: HSF Stories Detail|last=|first=|date=|website=www.hsf.net|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-13}}</ref> [[List of Texas A&M University presidents|President of Texas A&M University]]\nFile:Mireya Moscoso in 2012.jpg|[[Mireya Moscoso]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.councilwomenworldleaders.org/mireya-moscoso.html|title=Mireya Moscoso|website=Council of Women World Leaders|language=en|access-date=2019-12-13}}</ref> [[List of heads of state of Panama|President of Panama]] from 1999 to 2004. First female President\nFile:John L. Mica 113th Congress.jpg|[[John Mica]]\nFile:Flickr - nicogenin - 66\u00e8me Festival de Venise (Mostra) - Sylvester Stallone (26).jpg|[[Sylvester Stallone]] American Actor\nFile:StevenBauer08.jpg|[[Steven Bauer]] American-Cuban Actor\nFile:Glenn Howerton (9365867002).jpg|[[Glenn Howerton]] American Actor\nFile:Oscar Isaac by Gage Skidmore.jpg|[[Oscar Isaac]] American Actor and SInger\nFile:Ra\u00fal Iba\u00f1ez on September 9, 2012.jpg|[[Ra\u00fal Iba\u00f1ez|Raul Ibanez]] Professional American Baseball Player\nFile:Mike Piazza answers a question during the HOF news conference.jpg|[[Mike Piazza]] Former American Professional Baseball Player\nFile:Steve Carlton 1995.jpg|[[Steve Carlton]] Former American Professional Baseball Player\nFile:Polanco-crop.jpg|[[Pl\u00e1cido Polanco]] American-Dominican professional baseball player\nFile:2013 Imagen Foundation Awards, Natalie Martinez.jpg|[[Natalie Martinez]] American Actress and Model\nFile:Harry Wayne Casey 2017.jpg|[[Harry Wayne Casey|Harry Wayne Case]]y American Musician          \n</gallery>\n\n== References 