{"title_page": "Stan White (quarterback)", "text_new": "{{other people|Stan White}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n|name= Stan White\n|image= \n|image_size= \n|caption=\n|position= [[Quarterback]]\n|number=\n|birth_date= {{Birth date and age|1971|8|14}}\n|birth_place=[[Birmingham, Alabama]]\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n|draftyear=\n|draftround=\n|draftpick=\n|undraftedyear= 1994\n|high_school=[[Hoover High School (Alabama)|W. A. Berry]] ([[Hoover, Alabama]])\n|college= [[Auburn Tigers football|Auburn]]\n|pastteams=\n*[[New York Giants]] ({{NFL Year|1994|1997}})\n*[[London Monarchs]] (1998)\n|statlabel1=\n|statvalue1=\n|statlabel2=\n|statvalue2=\n|statlabel3=\n|statvalue3=\n|nfl= WHI517926\n|pfr=\n|highlights=\n*Auburn all-time #1 passer (8,016 yards)\n* [[1990 Peach Bowl]] MVP\n* 1994 [[Senior Bowl]] MVP\n|HOF=\n|CollegeHOF=\n}}\n\n'''Stan White''' (born August 14, 1971) is a former [[American football]] [[quarterback]].\n\n==Football career==\n\n===High school and college===\nA graduate of [[Hoover High School (Alabama)|W. A. Berry High School]] in [[Hoover, Alabama]]. He went on to play quarterback at [[Auburn University]] where he [[Starting lineup|started]] every game from his freshman year until his senior year, a total of 45 straight games. He was named permanent [[team captain]] on Auburn\u2019s undefeated [[1993 Auburn Tigers football team|1993 team]] that went 11\u20130 and was also named to Auburn\u2019s Team of the Decade for the 1990s.\n\n===NFL===\nWhite was signed by the [[New York Giants]] as a free agent in 1994 and remained with the team until 1997.\n\n===WLAF===\nIn 1997, he was allocated by the Giants to the [[London Monarchs]] of the [[World League of American Football]] (WLAF).\n\n==Retirement==\nWhite returned home to Birmingham in 1998 and now owns a [[State Farm Insurance]] and Financial Services Agency in Birmingham.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kevinderryberry.com/Stan%20White%20.htm|title=Stan White  Former Auburn Football Great|work=kevinderryberry.com|accessdate=2008-11-23}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001 White became the [[radio]] [[color commentator]] for the Auburn Network's football broadcasts. White also makes appearances around the [[Southern United States|South]] as a [[public speaker]], along with [[Jay Barker]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tgasports.com/football/player.php?pid=90|title=Stan White |work=TGA Speakers|publisher=The Todd Greene Agency|accessdate=29 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn August 30, 2011, White became co-host of a daily morning drive time sports call in show with Alabama broadcaster [[Eli Gold]] on [[WPYA|WZNN]] in [[Birmingham, Alabama]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Auburn Tigers quarterback navbox}}\n{{London Monarchs quarterback navbox}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:White, Stan}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American color commentators]]\n[[Category:American football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:American motivational speakers]]\n[[Category:Auburn Tigers football players]]\n[[Category:Auburn Tigers football broadcasters]]\n[[Category:London Monarchs players]]\n[[Category:New York Giants players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Birmingham, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Alabama]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people|Stan White}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n|name= Stan White\n|image= \n|image_size= \n|caption=\n|position= [[Quarterback]]\n|number=\n|birth_date= {{Birth date and age|1971|8|14}}\n|birth_place=[[Birmingham, Alabama]]\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n|draftyear=\n|draftround=\n|draftpick=\n|undraftedyear= 1994\n|high_school=[[Hoover High School (Alabama)|W. A. Berry]] ([[Hoover, Alabama]])\n|college= [[Auburn Tigers football|Auburn]]\n|pastteams=\n*[[New York Giants]] ({{NFL Year|1994|1997}})\n*[[London Monarchs]] (1998)\n|statlabel1=\n|statvalue1=\n|statlabel2=\n|statvalue2=\n|statlabel3=\n|statvalue3=\n|nfl= WHI517926\n|pfr=\n|highlights=\n*Auburn all-time #1 passer (8,016 yards)\n* [[1990 Peach Bowl]] MVP\n* 1994 [[Senior Bowl]] MVP\n|HOF=\n|CollegeHOF=\n}}\n\n'''Stan White''' (born August 14, 1971) is a former [[American football]] [[quarterback]].\n\n==Football career==\n\n===High school and college===\nA graduate of [[Hoover High School (Alabama)|W. A. Berry High School]] in [[Hoover, Alabama]]. He went on to play quarterback at [[Auburn University]] where he [[Starting lineup|started]] every game from his freshman year until his senior year, a total of 45 straight games. He was named permanent [[team captain]] on Auburn\u2019s undefeated [[1993 Auburn Tigers football team|1993 team]] that went 11\u20130 and was also named to Auburn\u2019s Team of the Decade for the 1990s.\n\n===NFL===\nWhite was signed by the [[New York Giants]] as a free agent in 1994 and remained with the team until 1997.\n\n===WLAF===\nIn 1997, he was allocated by the Giants to the [[London Monarchs]] of the [[World League of American Football]] (WLAF).\n\n==Retirement==\nWhite returned home to Birmingham in 1998 and now owns a [[State Farm Insurance]] and Financial Services Agency in Birmingham.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kevinderryberry.com/Stan%20White%20.htm|title=Stan White  Former Auburn Football Great|work=kevinderryberry.com|accessdate=2008-11-23}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001 White became the [[radio]] [[color commentator]] for the Auburn Network's football broadcasts. White also makes appearances around the [[Southern United States|South]] as a [[public speaker]], along with [[Jay Barker]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.footballspeakers.com/h/index.php?pid=56219&name=Jay-Barker-and-Stan-White|title=Jay Barker and Stan White |work=Football Speakers|publisher=The Todd Greene Agency|accessdate=2008-11-23}}</ref>\n\nOn August 30, 2011, White became co-host of a daily morning drive time sports call in show with Alabama broadcaster [[Eli Gold]] on [[WPYA|WZNN]] in [[Birmingham, Alabama]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Auburn Tigers quarterback navbox}}\n{{London Monarchs quarterback navbox}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:White, Stan}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American color commentators]]\n[[Category:American football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:American motivational speakers]]\n[[Category:Auburn Tigers football players]]\n[[Category:Auburn Tigers football broadcasters]]\n[[Category:London Monarchs players]]\n[[Category:New York Giants players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Birmingham, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Alabama]]\n", "name_user": "Gunbirddriver", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRetirement:updated citation and link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stan_White_(quarterback)"}
{"title_page": "Bajrang Lal Takhar", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian rower}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| honorific_prefix = [[Naib Subedar]]\n| name = Bajrang Lal Takhar\n| honorific_suffix = [[Padma Shri]]\n| sport = [[Rowing_(sport)|Rowing]]\n| birth_place = [[Sikar District]], [[Rajasthan]], [[India]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1981|01|05}}\n| medaltemplates = {{MedalCountry | {{IND}} }}\n{{MedalSport| Men's [[Rowing (sport)|rowing]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Asian Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[Rowing at the 2010 Asian Games|2010 Guangzhou]]|Single sculls}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[Rowing at the 2006 Asian Games|2006 Doha]]|Single sculls}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[Rowing at the 2014 Asian Games \u2013 Men's coxed eight|2014 Incheon]]| Eight}}\n| module = {{Infobox military person|embed=yes\n   | allegiance      = {{Flag|India}}\n   | branch          = {{Army|India}}\n   | serviceyears    = \n   | rank            = [[File:Naib Subedar - Naib Risaldar of the Indian Army.svg|25px]] [[Naib Subedar]]\n   | unit            = [[Rajputana Rifles]]\n   | awards      = [[File:IND Padma Shri BAR.png|30px]] [[Padma Shri]]\n}}\n}}\n\n[[Naib subedar|Naib Subedar]] '''Bajrang Lal Takhar''' (born 5 January 1981 in [[Sikar district]], [[Rajasthan]]) is an [[India]]n [[Rowing (sport)|rower]] who won the first individual rowing Gold medal for India at the [[2010 Asian Games]] held in [[Guangzhou]]. Takhar is a [[Naib Subedar]] in the [[Rajputana Rifles]] regiment of the [[Indian Army]].\n\n== Rowing career ==\n\nBajrang Lal won the first individual rowing silver medal for India at the 2006 Asian Games held in Doha<ref name=\"zeenews.com\">http://www.zeenews.com/news461184.html</ref> He contested in the men's single sculls rowing event at the [[2008 Summer Olympics]] in [[Beijing]], but failed to reach the finals. He finished with a rank of 21.\n\nHe then went on to bag gold at the Asian Championships in Korea last year 2007. He won the quota place by winning gold at the Asian qualifying championships in Shanghai.<ref name=\"zeenews.com\"/>\n\nHe has won two gold medals in the single and double scull races in [[South Asian Games 2006]].\n\nIn November 2010, he won the first individual rowing Gold medal for India at the [[2010 Asian Games]] held in [[Guangzhou]].\n\n== Awards ==\n* 2008 \u2013 [[Arjun Award]] by Govt of India.<ref>[http://www.naitindia.com/detail.php?n_id=13478 Dainik Navjyoti]{{Dead link|date=June 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* 2013 \u2013 [[Padma Shri]] India's fourth highest civilian award from the Government of India.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.pib.nic.in/newsite/erelease.aspx|title= Padma Awards|publisher=pib|date= 27 January 2013 |accessdate= 27 January 2013 }}</ref>\n\n== Rowing records of Takhar ==\n*16/08\tMen's Single Sculls Final Ranking\t(21st)\n*15/08\tMen's Single Sculls Final D\t7:09.73 (3rd)\n*13/08\tMen's Single Sculls Semifinal \u2013 Heat 3\t7:23.00 (4th)\n*11/08\tMen's Single Sculls Quarterfinal \u2013 Heat 4\t7:19.01 (5th)\n*09/08\tMen's Single Sculls Preliminary Round \u2013 Heat 4\t7:39.91 (3rd)\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://au.sports.yahoo.com/olympics/athletes/profile/-/205942/bajranglal-takhar Bajranglal Takhar on Yahoo sports] \n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Takhar, Bajranglal}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Indian male rowers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Rajasthan]]\n[[Category:Rajasthani people]]\n[[Category:Olympic rowers of India]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 2008 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:People from Sikar district]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Rajasthan]]\n[[Category:Asian Games gold medalists for India]]\n[[Category:Asian Games silver medalists for India]]\n[[Category:Asian Games bronze medalists for India]]\n[[Category:Asian Games medalists in rowing]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 2006 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 2010 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 2014 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Shri in sports]]\n\n{{India-rowing-bio-stub}}\n{{India-mil-bio-stub}}\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2006 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2010 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2014 Asian Games]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian rower}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name               = Bajrang Lal Takhar\n| sport              = [[Rowing_(sport)|Rowing]]\n| birth_place        = [[Sikar District]], [[Rajasthan]], [[India]]\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1981|01|05}}\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalCountry | {{IND}} }}\n{{MedalSport| Men's [[Rowing (sport)|rowing]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Asian Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[Rowing at the 2010 Asian Games|2010 Guangzhou]]|Single sculls}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[Rowing at the 2006 Asian Games|2006 Doha]]|Single sculls}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[Rowing at the 2014 Asian Games \u2013 Men's coxed eight|2014 Incheon]]| Eight}}\n}}\n\n'''Bajrang Lal Takhar''' (born 5 January 1981 in [[Sikar district]], [[Rajasthan]]) is an [[India]]n [[Rowing (sport)|rower]] who won the first individual rowing Gold medal for India at the [[2010 Asian Games]] held in [[Guangzhou]]. Takhar is a [[Naib Subedar]] in the [[Rajputana Rifles]] regiment of the [[Indian Army]].\n\n== Rowing career ==\n\nBajrang Lal won the first individual rowing silver medal for India at the 2006 Asian Games held in Doha<ref name=\"zeenews.com\">http://www.zeenews.com/news461184.html</ref> He contested in the men's single sculls rowing event at the [[2008 Summer Olympics]] in [[Beijing]], but failed to reach the finals. He finished with a rank of 21.\n\nHe then went on to bag gold at the Asian Championships in Korea last year 2007. He won the quota place by winning gold at the Asian qualifying championships in Shanghai.<ref name=\"zeenews.com\"/>\n\nHe has won two gold medals in the single and double scull races in [[South Asian Games 2006]].\n\nIn November 2010, he won the first individual rowing Gold medal for India at the [[2010 Asian Games]] held in [[Guangzhou]].\n\n== Awards ==\n* 2008 \u2013 [[Arjun Award]] by Govt of India.<ref>[http://www.naitindia.com/detail.php?n_id=13478 Dainik Navjyoti]{{Dead link|date=June 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* 2013 \u2013 [[Padma Shri]] India's fourth highest civilian award from the Government of India.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.pib.nic.in/newsite/erelease.aspx|title= Padma Awards|publisher=pib|date= 27 January 2013 |accessdate= 27 January 2013 }}</ref>\n\n== Rowing records of Takhar ==\n*16/08\tMen's Single Sculls Final Ranking\t(21st)\n*15/08\tMen's Single Sculls Final D\t7:09.73 (3rd)\n*13/08\tMen's Single Sculls Semifinal \u2013 Heat 3\t7:23.00 (4th)\n*11/08\tMen's Single Sculls Quarterfinal \u2013 Heat 4\t7:19.01 (5th)\n*09/08\tMen's Single Sculls Preliminary Round \u2013 Heat 4\t7:39.91 (3rd)\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://au.sports.yahoo.com/olympics/athletes/profile/-/205942/bajranglal-takhar Bajranglal Takhar on Yahoo sports] \n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Takhar, Bajranglal}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Indian male rowers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Rajasthan]]\n[[Category:Rajasthani people]]\n[[Category:Olympic rowers of India]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 2008 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:People from Sikar district]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Rajasthan]]\n[[Category:Asian Games gold medalists for India]]\n[[Category:Asian Games silver medalists for India]]\n[[Category:Asian Games bronze medalists for India]]\n[[Category:Asian Games medalists in rowing]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 2006 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 2010 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 2014 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Shri in sports]]\n\n{{India-rowing-bio-stub}}\n{{India-mil-bio-stub}}\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2006 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:Medalists a