{"title_page": "Sigur\u00f0ur Ingi J\u00f3hannsson", "text_new": "{{Icelandic name|Sigur\u00f0ur}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name\t\t\t= Sigur\u00f0ur Ingi J\u00f3hannsson\n| image\t\t\t= Sigur\u00f0ur Ingi J\u00f3hannsson 2016 (cropped).png\n| office1\t\t= [[Minister of the Interior (Iceland)|Minister of Transport and Local Government]] \n| term_start1\t\t= 30 November 2017\n| term_end1\t\t= \n| primeminister1\t= [[Katr\u00edn Jakobsd\u00f3ttir]] \n| predecessor1\t\t= [[J\u00f3n Gunnarsson]]\n| office2\t\t= [[Progressive Party (Iceland)|Chairman of the Progressive Party]]\n| deputy2= [[Lilja D\u00f6gg Alfre\u00f0sd\u00f3ttir]]\n| term_start2\t\t= 2 October 2016\n| term_end2\t\t= \n| predecessor2\t\t= [[Sigmundur Dav\u00ed\u00f0 Gunnlaugsson]]\n| successor2\t\t= \n| office3\t\t= 26th [[Prime Minister of Iceland]]\n| term_start3\t\t= 7 April 2016\n| term_end3\t\t= 11 January 2017\n| president3\t\t= [[\u00d3lafur Ragnar Gr\u00edmsson]]<br />[[Gu\u00f0ni Th. J\u00f3hannesson]]\n| predecessor3\t\t= [[Sigmundur Dav\u00ed\u00f0 Gunnlaugsson]]\n| successor3\t\t= [[Bjarni Benediktsson (born 1970)|Bjarni Benediktsson]]\n| office4= [[Minister of Fisheries and Agriculture (Iceland)|Minister of Fisheries and Agriculture]]\n| primeminister4= [[Sigmundur Dav\u00ed\u00f0 Gunnlaugsson]]\n| term_start4= 23 May 2013\n| term_end4= 7 April 2016\n| predecessor4= [[Steingr\u00edmur J. Sigf\u00fasson]]\n| office5\t\t= [[Minister for the Environment and Natural Resources (Iceland)|Minister of the Environment and Natural Resources]]\n| term_start5\t\t= 23 May 2013\n| term_end5\t\t= 31 December 2014\n| primeminister5 = [[Sigmundur Dav\u00ed\u00f0 Gunnlaugsson]]\n| predecessor5 = [[Svand\u00eds Svavarsd\u00f3ttir]]\n| successor5\t\t= [[Sigr\u00fan Magn\u00fasd\u00f3ttir]]\n| birth_date\t\t= {{birth date and age|df=y|1962|4|20}}\n| birth_place\t\t= [[Selfoss (town)|Selfoss]], [[Iceland]]\n| death_date\t\t= \n| death_place\t\t= \n| party\t\t\t= [[Progressive Party (Iceland)|Progressive Party]]\n| spouse\t\t= Ingibj\u00f6rg Elsa Ingjaldsd\u00f3ttir\n| children\t\t= 5\n}}\n\n'''Sigur\u00f0ur Ingi J\u00f3hannsson''' (born 20 April 1962) is an Icelandic politician, who was the [[Prime Minister of Iceland]] from April 2016 to January 2017. He is the chairman of the [[Progressive Party (Iceland)|Progressive Party]].\n\nSigur\u00f0ur was appointed as the Prime Minister on 7 April 2016 following the resignation of [[Sigmundur Dav\u00ed\u00f0 Gunnlaugsson]] in the wake of revelations contained in the [[Panama Papers]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2016/04/06/business/06reuters-panama-tax-iceland-primeminister.html |title=Iceland Government Coalition Appoints Johannsson as New PM-Progressive Party MP |publisher=The New York Times |work=The New York Times |date=6 April 2016 |accessdate=6 April 2016 |author=Reuters}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://icelandreview.com/news/2016/04/06/sigurdur-ingi-johannsson-icelands-new-pm |title=Sigur\u00f0ur Ingi J\u00f3hannsson Iceland\u2019s New PM | work=Iceland Review |date=6 April 2016 |accessdate=6 April 2016 |author=Hafstad, Vala}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2016/04/06/world/europe/ap-eu-offshore-accounts-iceland.html |title=Johannsson to Seek Approval to Become Iceland's Next PM |work=The New York Times |date=6 April 2016 |accessdate=6 April 2016 |author=THE ASSOCIATED PRESS}}</ref> He was elected as chairman of the [[Progressive Party (Iceland)|Progressive Party]] on 2 October that year, narrowly ahead of incumbent chairman Sigmundur Dav\u00ed\u00f0.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruv.is/frett/sigurdur-ingi-kjorinn-formadur-framsoknar|title=Sigur\u00f0ur Ingi kj\u00f6rinn forma\u00f0ur Frams\u00f3knar|date=2016-10-02|access-date=2016-10-02}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 October 2016, due to the results of the [[2016 Icelandic parliamentary election|parliamentary election]] held the previous day on 29 October 2016, Sigur\u00f0ur announced his pending resignation as Prime Minister.<ref>[https://www.adn.com/arctic/2016/10/31/icelands-prime-minister-resigns-after-pirate-party-makes-strong-gains/ Iceland\u2019s prime minister resigns, after Pirate Party makes strong gains] Alaska News, 1 November 2016. Retrieved 3 November 2016</ref> He officially left office on 11 January 2017 and was succeeded by [[Bjarni Benediktsson (born 1970)|Bjarni Benediktsson]].\n\n== Biography ==\nHe grew up on a farm in Southern Iceland, trained as a veterinarian at the [[Royal Veterinary and Agricultural University]] in Copenhagen and opened a veterinarian practice specializing on farm animals after returning home to Iceland. He was since elected as chairman of the Veterinarian Association of Iceland and also ran the family farm for a number of years. \n\nSigur\u00f0ur served as [[Ministry of Fisheries and Agriculture (Iceland)|Minister of Fisheries and Agriculture]] 2013\u20132016. He is a former [[Minister for the Environment and Natural Resources (Iceland)|Minister for the Environment and Natural Resources]], a role which he held jointly with Fisheries and Agriculture until [[Sigr\u00fan Magn\u00fasd\u00f3ttir]] was appointed Minister for the Environment and Natural Resources at the end of 2014.\n\nAs a result of the [[2016 Icelandic anti-government protests|ousting]] of prime minister [[Sigmundur Dav\u00ed\u00f0 Gunnlaugsson]] following the [[Panama Papers]] scandal, the [[Progressive Party (Iceland)|Progressive Party]] announced Sigur\u00f0ur as the interim prime minister pending the early election in the fall of 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://icelandreview.com/news/2016/04/06/sigurdur-ingi-johannsson-icelands-new-pm|title=Sigur\u00f0ur Ingi J\u00f3hannsson Iceland\u2019s New PM|last=Hafstad|first=Vala|date=2016-04-06|website=Iceland Review|language=en|access-date=2016-05-28}}</ref>\n\nHe has been Minister of Transportation and Local Government since the 30 November 2017.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.althingi.is/cv.php4?nfaerslunr=726 Biography of Sigur\u00f0ur on Althing]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sigmundur Dav\u00ed\u00f0 Gunnlaugsson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Leader of the [[Progressive Party (Iceland)|Progressive Party]]|years=2016\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sigmundur Dav\u00ed\u00f0 Gunnlaugsson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prime Minister of Iceland]]|years=2016\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Bjarni Benediktsson (born 1970)|Bjarni Benediktsson]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Prime Ministers of Iceland}}\n{{Members of Althing}}\n{{Cabinet of Sigmundur Dav\u00ed\u00f0 Gunnlaugsson}}\n{{Cabinet of Katr\u00edn Jakobsd\u00f3ttir}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Johannsson, Sigurdur Ingi}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Agriculture ministers of Iceland|Sigurdur Ingi Johannsson]]\n[[Category:Environment ministers of Iceland|Sigurdur Ingi Johannsson]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Progressive Party (Iceland) politicians|Sigurdur Ingi Johannsson]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Iceland|Sigurdur Ingi Johannsson]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Iceland|Sigurdur Ingi Johannsson]]\n\n\n{{Iceland-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Icelandic name|Sigur\u00f0ur}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name\t\t\t= Sigur\u00f0ur Ingi J\u00f3hannsson\n| image\t\t\t= Sigur\u00f0ur Ingi J\u00f3hannsson 2016 (cropped).png\n| office1\t\t= [[Minister of the Interior (Iceland)|Minister of Transport and Local Government]] \n| term_start1\t\t= 30 November 2017\n| term_end1\t\t= \n| primeminister1\t= [[Katr\u00edn Jakobsd\u00f3ttir]] \n| predecessor1\t\t= [[J\u00f3n Gunnarsson]]\n| office2\t\t= [[Progressive Party (Iceland)|Chairman of the Progressive Party]]\n| deputy2= [[Lilja D\u00f6gg Alfre\u00f0sd\u00f3ttir]]\n| term_start2\t\t= 2 October 2016\n| term_end2\t\t= \n| predecessor2\t\t= [[Sigmundur Dav\u00ed\u00f0 Gunnlaugsson]]\n| successor2\t\t= \n| office3\t\t= 26th [[Prime Minister of Iceland]]\n| term_start3\t\t= 7 April 2016\n| term_end3\t\t= 11 January 2017\n| president3\t\t= [[\