/06/sigurdur-ingi-johannsson-icelands-new-pm |title=Sigur\u00f0ur Ingi J\u00f3hannsson Iceland\u2019s New PM | work=Iceland Review |date=6 April 2016 |accessdate=6 April 2016 |author=Hafstad, Vala}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2016/04/06/world/europe/ap-eu-offshore-accounts-iceland.html |title=Johannsson to Seek Approval to Become Iceland's Next PM |work=The New York Times |date=6 April 2016 |accessdate=6 April 2016 |author=THE ASSOCIATED PRESS}}</ref> He was elected as chairman of the [[Progressive Party (Iceland)|Progressive Party]] on 2 October that year, narrowly ahead of incumbent chairman Sigmundur Dav\u00ed\u00f0.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ruv.is/frett/sigurdur-ingi-kjorinn-formadur-framsoknar|title=Sigur\u00f0ur Ingi kj\u00f6rinn forma\u00f0ur Frams\u00f3knar|date=2016-10-02|access-date=2016-10-02}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 October 2016, due to the results of the [[2016 Icelandic parliamentary election|parliamentary election]] held the previous day on 29 October 2016, Sigur\u00f0ur announced his pending resignation as Prime Minister.<ref>[https://www.adn.com/arctic/2016/10/31/icelands-prime-minister-resigns-after-pirate-party-makes-strong-gains/ Iceland\u2019s prime minister resigns, after Pirate Party makes strong gains] Alaska News, 1 November 2016. Retrieved 3 November 2016</ref> He officially left office on 11 January 2017 and was succeeded by [[Bjarni Benediktsson (born 1970)|Bjarni Benediktsson]].\n\n== Biography ==\nHe grew up on a farm in Southern Iceland, trained as a veterinarian at the [[Royal Veterinary and Agricultural University]] in Copenhagen and opened a veterinarian praxis specializih on farm animals after returning home to Iceland. He was since elected as chairman of the Veterinarian Association of Iceland and also ran the family farm for a number of years. \n\nSigur\u00f0ur served as [[Ministry of Fisheries and Agriculture (Iceland)|Minister of Fisheries and Agriculture]] 2013\u20132016. He is a former [[Minister for the Environment and Natural Resources (Iceland)|Minister for the Environment and Natural Resources]], a role which he held jointly with Fisheries and Agriculture until [[Sigr\u00fan Magn\u00fasd\u00f3ttir]] was appointed Minister for the Environment and Natural Resources at the end of 2014.\n\nAs a result of the [[2016 Icelandic anti-government protests|ousting]] of prime minister [[Sigmundur Dav\u00ed\u00f0 Gunnlaugsson]] following the [[Panama Papers]] scandal, the [[Progressive Party (Iceland)|Progressive Party]] announced Sigur\u00f0ur as the interim prime minister pending the early election in the fall of 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://icelandreview.com/news/2016/04/06/sigurdur-ingi-johannsson-icelands-new-pm|title=Sigur\u00f0ur Ingi J\u00f3hannsson Iceland\u2019s New PM|last=Hafstad|first=Vala|date=2016-04-06|website=Iceland Review|language=en|access-date=2016-05-28}}</ref>\n\nHe has been Minister of Transportation and Local Government since the 30 November 2017.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.althingi.is/cv.php4?nfaerslunr=726 Biography of Sigur\u00f0ur on Althing]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sigmundur Dav\u00ed\u00f0 Gunnlaugsson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Leader of the [[Progressive Party (Iceland)|Progressive Party]]|years=2016\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sigmundur Dav\u00ed\u00f0 Gunnlaugsson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prime Minister of Iceland]]|years=2016\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Bjarni Benediktsson (born 1970)|Bjarni Benediktsson]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Prime Ministers of Iceland}}\n{{Members of Althing}}\n{{Cabinet of Sigmundur Dav\u00ed\u00f0 Gunnlaugsson}}\n{{Cabinet of Katr\u00edn Jakobsd\u00f3ttir}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Johannsson, Sigurdur Ingi}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Agriculture ministers of Iceland|Sigurdur Ingi Johannsson]]\n[[Category:Environment ministers of Iceland|Sigurdur Ingi Johannsson]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Progressive Party (Iceland) politicians|Sigurdur Ingi Johannsson]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Iceland|Sigurdur Ingi Johannsson]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Iceland|Sigurdur Ingi Johannsson]]\n\n\n{{Iceland-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Shield543", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixed 2 typos \"praxis -> practice\", \"specializh -> specializing\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sigur%C3%B0ur_Ingi_J%C3%B3hannsson"}
{"title_page": "Nintendo Switch Online", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox video game online service\n|title = Nintendo Switch Online\n|logo = File:Nintendo Switch Online logo.svg\n|developer = [[Nintendo]]\n|type = Online service\n|status = Online\n|released = {{start date and age|2018|09|19}} \n|members = Over 15 million (as of January 2020) \n|platform = [[Nintendo Switch]]\n|website = {{URL|https://www.nintendo.com/switch/online-service/}}\n}}\n\n'''Nintendo Switch Online''' is a suite of features on the [[Nintendo Switch]] [[video game console]] requiring purchase of a [[subscription]]. Nintendo Switch Online features include [[online multiplayer]], cloud saving, [[voice chat]], access to a library of [[Nintendo Entertainment System]] (NES) and [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System]] (SNES) games, as well as other promotions and offers. Following a period where some of its features were available to all users at no charge, the subscription service officially launched on September 19, 2018.\n\nThe service is Nintendo's third generation online service after [[Nintendo Wi-Fi Connection]] and [[Nintendo Network]].\n\n== History ==\nThe Nintendo Switch was formally announced in January 2017, with its release on March 3, 2017. Nintendo stated in its pre-release announcements that the system would eventually require purchase of a paid \"online service\", but that they would be available to all users at no charge until the service launched. Features announced included a companion smartphone app, as well as access to a free [[Nintendo Entertainment System]] game per-month. The service was initially planned for late 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://time.com/4634346/nintendo-switch-online-subscription-mulitplayer-2017/|title=Nintendo Is Launching a New Online Service for the Switch|last=Eadicicco|first=Lisa|date=January 13, 2017|website=Time|language=en|access-date=December 1, 2018}}</ref> By June 2017, Nintendo pushed back the service's release until 2018, but did establish the pricing plans for the service, with an average annual price of {{USD|20}}, depending on region.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2017-06-02-nintendo-switch-online-service-to-launch-in-2018|title=Nintendo Switch online service pushed back to 2018|work=GamesIndustry.biz|access-date=December 1, 2018|language=en}}</ref> Then-Nintendo of America president [[Reggie Fils-Aim\u00e9]] explained that the delays were to ensure that the service was \"world-class\", and had enough of its announced functionality available on-launch to justify its cost.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.polygon.com/e3/2017/6/15/15811288/nintendo-switch-online-delays-reggie-fils-aime-interview-e3-2017 | title = Nintendo boss explains why Switch's online services were delayed | first = Chelsea | last = Stark | date = June 15, 2017 | accessdate = June 15, 2017 | website = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170615210755/https://www.polygon.com/e3/2017/6/15/15811288/nintendo-switch-online-delays-reggie-fils-aime-interview-e3-2017 | archivedate = June 15, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> Nintendo aimed for a lower price point in comparison to [[PlayStation Plus]] and [[Xbox Live Gold]], as the service does not include the same range of features as these subscription services provide.<ref name=\"gamespot-switchsubprice\">{{cite web|title=Nintendo Switch's Online Subscription Service May Cost Less Than You Expect|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/nintendo-switchs-online-subscription-service-may-c/1100-6447470/|website=GameSpot|accessdate=February 1, 2017|date=February 1, 2017|first=Chris|last=Pereira|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170212060238/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/nintendo-switchs-online-subscription-service-may-c/1100-6447470/|archivedate=February 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.vg247.com/2017/02/01/switch-online-service-will-run-between-17-50-and-26-50-a-year-in-japan/ | title = Nintendo Switch Online Service will run between $17.50 and $26.50 a year in Japan | first = Stephany | last = Nunneley | date = February 1, 2017 | accessdate = February 1, 2017 | website = [[VG247]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170201202848/http://www.vg247.com/2017/02/01/switch-online-service-will-run-between-17-50-and-26-50-a-year-in-japan/ | archivedate = February 1, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> Then-Nintendo president [[Tatsumi Kimishima]] stated that the price point was a subject of importance in designing the Switch's online services, and that regardless of what competitors were doing, \"it's a matter of getting our content to the consumer at a price point that would make them happy, and then we're willing to look at what else we can do going forward.\"<ref name=\"time kimishima\"/><ref name=\"time kimishima\">{{Cite web | url = http://time.com/4662446/nintendo-president-switch-interview/ | title = 19 Things Nintendo's President Told Us About Switch and More | first = Matt | last = Peckham | date = February 7, 2017 | accessdate = February 7, 2017 | website = [[Time (magazine)|Time]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170207192823/http://time.com/4662446/nintendo-president-switch-interview/ | archivedate = February 7, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe Nintendo Switch Online service was launched on September 19, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/9/18/17874798/nintendo-switch-online-launch-subscription|title=Nintendo Switch Online is live \u2014 here\u2019s how to join|work=The Verge|access-date=December 1, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/9/18/17873926/nintendo-switch-online-release-date-time-edt-pdt-downtime|title=What time will Nintendo Switch Online launch?|work=Polygon|access-date=December 1, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/9/12/17850516/nintendo-switch-online-service-release-date|title=The Nintendo Switch online service is launching on September 18th|work=The Verge|access-date=November 30, 2018}}</ref> A [[Nintendo Direct]] two days before the release detailed the full set of features that would be part of the Online service, including a larger and persistent library of NES games for subscribers (with 20 available on launch, and more to be added on an ongoing basis), as well as cloud save support.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/nintendo-switch-online-service-more-details-reveal/1100-6461758/|title=Nintendo Switch Online Service: More Details Revealed In Nintendo Direct|last=Knezevic|first=Kevin|date=September 17, 2018|website=GameSpot|language=en-US|access-date=December 1, 2018}}</ref> The initial launch covered 43 markets, with more markets expected to follow later.<ref name=\"NOA support\">{{cite web | url=https://en-americas-support.nintendo.com/app/answers/detail/a_id/41953/~/nintendo-switch-online-service-and-feature-availability-by-country | title=Nintendo of America cites 8 markets in the Americas | publisher=Nintendo of America | accessdate=March 4, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"NOE support\">{{cite web | url=https://www.nintendo.co.uk/Support/Nintendo-Switch/Nintendo-Switch-Online/Nintendo-Switch-Online-Service-FAQ-1442566.html | title=Nintendo UK cites 32 markets: 31 European countries and South Africa | publisher=Nintendo UK | accessdate=March 4, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"NAL support\">{{cite web | url=https://www.nintendo.com.au/nintendo-switch/onlineservice/ | title=Nintendo Australia cites Australian and New Zealand markets | publisher=[[Nintendo Australia]] | accessdate=March 4, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"NCL support\">{{cite web | url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/hardware/switch/onlineservice/index.html | title=Nintendo Co., Ltd. cites Japanese market | publisher=Nintendo Co., Ltd. | accessdate=March 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, Nintendo Switch consoles imported to [[China]] started experiencing connectivity issues there, due to the Nintendo Switch Online service using [[Google]]'s servers, which are blocked in China.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.abacusnews.com/big-guns/gamers-china-cant-play-online-games-nintendo-switch-anymore/article/2166039|title=Gamers in China can\u2019t play online games on Nintendo Switch anymore|work=Abacus|access-date=December 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn March 28, 2019, [[Twitch (service)|Twitch]] announced that Twitch Prime members can claim up to a year of free Nintendo Switch Online membership between March 28, 2019 and January 20, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/3/28/18285489/nintendo-switch-online-free-twitch-prime|title=Get Nintendo Switch Online free for a year, with Twitch Prime|last=Good|first=Owen S.|date=2019-03-28|website=Polygon|access-date=2019-03-29}}</ref>\n\nThe service officially launched in [[South Korea]] and [[Hong Kong]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2019/02/nintendo_switch_online_to_launch_in_hong_kong_and_south_korea|title=Nintendo Switch Online To Launch In Hong Kong And South Korea|last=Lane|first=Gavin|date=February 20, 2019|website=Nintendo Life|language=en-GB|access-date=February 20, 2019}}</ref> on April 23, 2019.<ref name=\"NS cites KO & HK NSO details\" />\n\nOn September 4, 2019, Nintendo announced in a [[Nintendo Direct]] presentation that [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|Super NES]] games would be added to the service the following day under a separate app.<ref name=\"snes\">{{cite web |url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/9/4/20850054/nintendo-switch-online-snes-games-controller-nintendo-direct |title=SNES games coming to Nintendo Switch Online |last=Sarkar |first=Samit |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |date=September 4, 2019 |accessdate=September 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Usage===\nBy December 31, 2018, approximately three months after its launch, the service had gained more than eight million subscribers.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/02/01/nintendo-switch-online-surpasses-8-million-subscribers | title=  Nintendo Switch Online Surpasses 8 Million Subscribers | first = Adam | last= Bankhurst | date = January 31, 2019 | accessdate= January 31, 2019 | work = [[IGN]] }}</ref> Nintendo reported in late-April 2019 that the service had 9.8 million subscribers.<ref>{{Cite web |  url = https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2019-04-26-9-8-million-accounts-subscribe-to-nintendo-switch-online | title = 9.8 million accounts subscribe to Nintendo Switch Online  | first=  Tom |last= Phillips | date = April 26, 2019 | accessdate =April 26, 2019 | work = [[Eurogamer]] }}</ref> The service reached over 10 million subscribers by July 2019,<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2019-07-06-nintendo-switch-online-now-has-10-million-subscribers | title = Nintendo Switch Online now has 10 million subscribers  | first=  Wesley |last= Yin-Poole | date = July 6, 2019 | accessdate =July 6, 2019 | work = [[Eurogamer]]  }}</ref> and over 15 million by January 2020.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.videogameschronicle.com/news/nintendo-switch-online-tops-15-million-subscribers/ | title=  Nintendo Switch Online tops 15 million subscribers | first = Tom | last = Ivan | date = January 31, 2020 | accessdate = January 31, 2020 | work = [[Video Game Chronicle]] }}</ref>\n\n== Features ==\n=== Multiplayer ===\nNintendo Switch Online is required to access online multiplayer on the majority of titles. Some [[free-to-play]] multiplayer games, such as ''[[Fortnite Battle Royale]]'' and ''[[Warframe]]'', are exempt from this requirement, and can be played online freely without a subscription.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/9/14/17861300/fortnite-nintendo-switch-online|title=Fortnite for Switch won\u2019t require Nintendo\u2019s premium online service for play|work=Polygon|access-date=September 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/warframe-out-now-on-nintendo-switch-an-impressive-/1100-6463299/|title=Warframe Out Now On Nintendo Switch -- An Impressive Port That Surprised Us|last=Fillari|first=Alessandro|date=November 20, 2018|website=GameSpot|language=en-US|access-date=November 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Cloud saves ===\n[[Cloud storage]] allows save data for many games to be synchronized online, so it can be recovered if the user must move their [[Nintendo Account]] to a different Switch console or if they use multiple consoles.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/9/13/17856730/nintendo-switch-online-cloud-saves-explained|title=Cloud Saves are coming to the Nintendo Switch, here\u2019s how they\u2019ll work|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|access-date=November 30, 2018}}</ref> The feature is not supported for some games including those with certain forms of online functionality such as item trading and competitive rankings, citing concerns surrounding the possibility of abuse that could [[Cheating in video games|\"unfairly affect\"]] gameplay.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/nintendo-says-cheaters-are-why-some-switch-games-cant-backup-saves-online/|title=Nintendo says cheaters are why some Switch games can't backup saves online|last=Hollister|first=Sean|date=September 10, 2018|work=CNET|access-date=November 30, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nUsers will lose access to their cloud saves should they allow their subscription to lapse, though there is a grace period of six months to renew the subscription and recover them before they are purged.<ref name=\"ign online sept2018\">{{cite web | url = https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/09/14/nintendo-cloud-save-data-is-deleted-if-your-subscription-expires | title = Nintendo Cloud Save Data Is Deleted If Your Subscription Expires | first = Nick | last = Santangelo | date = September 14, 2018 | accessdate = September 17, 2018 | work = [[IGN]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/09/25/nintendo-will-let-you-recover-cloud-saves-up-to-6-months-after-your-switch-online-subscription-lapses | title = Nintendo Will Let You Recover Cloud Saves Up To 6 Months After Your Switch Online Subscription Lapses | first = Jonathan  | last = Dornbush  |date = September 25, 2018 | accessdate = September 25, 2018 | work = [[IGN]] }}</ref>\n\nAccording to the list below, there are currently '''{{#expr:{{table row counter|id=CloudSaveUnsupported|ignore=0}}}}''' games which do not support cloud save functionality.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://en-americas-support.nintendo.com/app/answers/detail/a_id/41267/~/which-nintendo-switch-titles-are-compatible-with-save-data-cloud-backup%3F |title=Which Nintendo Switch Titles Are Compatible with Save Data Cloud Backup? |website=[[Nintendo]] |accessdate=March 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\" id=\"CloudSaveUnsupported\"\n|+ {{Nowrap|List of Nintendo Switch titles which do not support cloud saves}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Additional information\n|-\n| ''[[1-2-Switch]]''\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Animal Crossing: New Horizons]]''\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Asphalt 9: Legends]]''\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Bass Pro Shops: The Strike]] \u2013 Championship Edition''\n| \n|-\n| ''Blade II \u2013 The Return of Evil''\n| \n|-\n| ''Bookbound Brigade''\n| \n|-\n| ''Cabela's: The Hunt \u2013 Championship Edition''\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Catan#Video games|Catan]]''\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Civilization VI]]''\n| \n|-\n| ''Color Zen Kids''\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Daemon X Machina]]''\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Dark Souls: Remastered]]''\n| \n|-\n| ''Dawn of the Breakers''\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Dead by Daylight]]''\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Death Mark]]''\n| \n|-\n| ''Dungeon Stars''\n| \n|-\n| ''Eternal Card Game''\n| \n|-\n| ''Exorder''\n| \n|-\n| ''[[FIFA 18]]''\n| \n|-\n| ''[[FIFA 19]]''\n| \n|-\n| ''[[FIFA 20]]''\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Fortnite Battle Royale]]''\n| \n|-\n| ''Gems of War''\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Go Vacation]]''\n| \n|-\n| ''In-Vert''\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Jumanji: The Video Game]]''\n| \n|-\n| ''Lanternium''\n| \n|-\n| ''Lightseekers''\n| \n|-\n| ''The Lord of the Rings: Adventure Card Game''\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Minecraft: Nintendo Switch Edition]]''\n| \n|-\n| ''Miniature \u2013 The Story Puzzle''\n| \n|-\n| ''Mistover''\n| \n|-\n| ''Modern Combat Blackout''\n| \n|-\n| ''[[NBA 2K Playgrounds 2]]''\n| \n|-\n| ''[[New Super Lucky's Tale]]''\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Nidhogg 2]]''\n| \n|-\n| ''No Time to Relax''\n| \n|-\n| ''Orbitblazers''\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Overwatch (video game)|Overwatch]]''\n| \n|-\n| ''Pixel Devil and the Broken Cartridge''\n| \n|-\n| [[Pok\u00e9mon: Let's Go, Pikachu! and Let's Go, Eevee!|''Pok\u00e9mon: Let's Go, Pikachu!'' and ''Let's Go, Eevee!'']]\n| \n|-\n| [[Pok\u00e9mon Sword and Shield|''Pok\u00e9mon Sword'' and ''Shield'']]\n| \n|-\n| ''[[The Raven Remastered]]''\n| \n|-\n| ''Robbie Swifthand and the Orb of Mysteries''\n| \n|-\n| ''Speaking Simulator''\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Splatoon 2]]''\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Super Dragon Ball Heroes: World Mission]]''\n| \n|-\n| ''Taimumari: Complete Edition''\n| \n|-\n| ''[[The Town of Light]]''\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Warface]]''\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Warhammer Age of Sigmar: Champions]]''\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Yu-Gi-Oh! Legacy of the Duelist: Link Evolution]]''\n| \n|}\n\n=== Communication ===\nUsers can [[voice chat]] through the Nintendo Switch Online mobile app on [[smartphone]]s. Voice chat functionality is not available natively through the Switch console; Fils-Aim\u00e9 justified the decision by explaining that \"Nintendo's approach is to do things differently. We have a much different suite of experiences than our competitors offer, and we do that in a different way. This creates a sort of yin and yang for our consumers. They're excited about cloud saves and legacy content but wish we might deliver voice chat a different way, for example.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2018/10/nintendo-president-our-future-is-as-an-entertainment-company/|title=Nintendo president: \"I compete for time,\" not against Xbox, PlayStation|work=Ars Technica|access-date=October 4, 2018|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n=== Classic games service ===\nPast Nintendo consoles (including [[Wii]], the [[Nintendo 3DS family]], and [[Wii U]]) with online functionality had offered games from Nintendo's older console libraries through the [[Virtual Console]], but would not use this for the Switch. Instead, Switch Online subscribers can access [[Nintendo Entertainment System]] (NES) and [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System]] (SNES) apps, both which feature a persistent and expanding library of classic titles from the systems. Access to the games are available as long as the user has an active subscription, and a user must connect to the internet at least once a week to continue to access the titles while offline. Games with multiplayer modes support both local and online play; online play functionality is a first for NES and SNES games.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://kotaku.com/nintendo-details-switch-online-service-will-be-20-yea-1795743981 | title = Nintendo Switch's Online Service Will Be $20/Year, Includes Classic Games [UPDATE] | first = Jason | last = Schreier | date = May 1, 2017 | accessdate = May 1, 2017 | website = [[Kotaku]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170602110956/http://kotaku.com/nintendo-details-switch-online-service-will-be-20-yea-1795743981 | archivedate = June 2, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://kotaku.com/nintendo-details-switch-online-service-will-be-20-yea-1795743981 | title = Nintendo Switch's Online Service Will Be $20/Year, Includes Classic Games | first = Jason | last = Schreier | date = June 1, 2017 | accessdate = June 2, 2017 | website = [[Kotaku]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170602110956/http://kotaku.com/nintendo-details-switch-online-service-will-be-20-yea-1795743981 | archivedate = June 2, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.vg247.com/2017/06/02/no-more-just-one-free-game-you-can-only-play-for-a-month-nintendo-changes-its-online-services-free-game-scheme/ | title = No more just one free game you can only play for a month: Nintendo changes its online service's free game scheme | first = Sharif | last = Saed | date = June 2, 2017 | accessdate = June 2, 2017 | website = [[VG247]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170602120036/http://www.vg247.com/2017/06/02/no-more-just-one-free-game-you-can-only-play-for-a-month-nintendo-changes-its-online-services-free-game-scheme/ | archivedate = June 2, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ign.com/articles/2018/09/17/nintendo-switch-online-nes-games-can-be-played-offline-for-up-to-seven-days | title = Nintendo Switch Online: Nes Games Can Be Played Offline For Up To Seven Days | first = Colin  |last = Stevens | date = September 17, 2018 | accessdate = September 17, 2018 | work = [[IGN]] }}</ref>\n\nCertain NES games released on the service between October 2018 to August 2019 also have an alternative version labeled \"SP\" (\"Extra\" in some regions) which either starts the player near the end of the game or starts the game with the maximum amount of items and lives. Most of the games released in both the Americas and PAL territories are the original NTSC-U versions, including their North American naming and 60&nbsp;Hz support. The Western NES variant of the software is available in South Korea, while the Japanese Family Computer variant is available in Hong Kong.<ref name=\"NS cites KO & HK NSO details\">{{cite web |url=https://nintendosoup.com/nintendo-switch-online-launches-april-23-in-south-korea-and-hong-kong-pricing-and-offers-announced/ |last=Nosuupu |first=Iggy |date=April 2, 2019 |title=Nintendo Switch Online Launches April 23 In South Korea And Hong Kong, Pricing And Offers Announced |website=NintendoSoup |accessdate=April 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring its first year, the Online service provided a new batch of NES games on a monthly basis. However, with the addition of SNES titles in September 2019, Nintendo stated that new NES and SNES games would no longer be made available on a regular schedule though would continue to expand both libraries over time.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamespot.com/articles/switch-wont-be-adding-new-nes-and-snes-games-in-mo/1100-6469688/ | title = Switch Won't Be Adding New NES And SNES Games In Monthly Batches Anymore | first = Kevin | last = Knezevic | date = September 6, 2019 | accessdate = September 6, 2019 | work = [[GameSpot]] }}</ref>\n\nThe service is home to several titles that were not available on the Virtual Console including ''[[Crystalis]]'', ''[[Journey to Silius]]'', ''[[Joe & Mac 2: Lost in the Tropics]]'' and ''[[Star Fox 2]]''. Some games saw their first rerelease in any form since their original debut such as ''[[Pro Wrestling (NES video game)|Pro Wrestling]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://retronauts.com/article/958/pro-wrestling-returns-as-nintendo-launches-its-online-service |title=Pro Wrestling returns as Nintendo launches its online service |last=Parish |first=Jeremy |website=[[Retronauts]] |date=September 19, 2018 |accessdate=January 28, 2020}}</ref> ''[[Vice: Project Doom]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/switch-onlines-free-nes-games-for-august-available/1100-6469286/ |title=Switch Online's Free NES Games For August Available Now |last=Knezevic |first=Kevin |work=[[GameSpot]] |date=August 23, 2019 |accessdate=January 28, 2020}}</ref> and ''[[Stunt Race FX]]''. The service also marks the first ever North American release of the SNES games ''[[Pop'n TwinBee]]'' and ''Smash Tennis''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.siliconera.com/next-nintendo-switch-online-nes-and-snes-games-include-popn-twinbee-and-smash-tennis/|title=New Nintendo Switch Online NES & SNES Games Arrive on February 19th|date=February 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== NES games ====\nWith the launch of the Nintendo Switch Online service on September 19, 2018, NES games were made available with 20 titles available at launch. Subscribers can access them through a dedicated app. Games available include:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+List of NES games on Nintendo Switch Online\n!Release date\n!Game\n!Publisher\n!NA/PAL/KR\n!JP/HK\n|-\n| rowspan=\"20\" |September 19, 2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/9/13/17856798/nintendo-switch-online-nes-games-list|title=Nintendo Switch Online has these 20 classic NES games|last=Good|first=Owen S.|date=September 13, 2018|website=Polygon|access-date=January 10, 2019}}</ref>\n|''[[Balloon Fight]]''\n|[[Nintendo]]\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|''[[Baseball (1983 video game)|Baseball]]''\n|Nintendo\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|''[[Donkey Kong (video game)|Donkey Kong]]''\n|Nintendo\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|''[[Double Dragon (video game)|Double Dragon]]''\n|[[Arc System Works]]\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|''[[Dr. Mario]]''\n|Nintendo\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|''[[Excitebike]]''\n|Nintendo\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|''[[Ghosts 'n Goblins (video game)|Ghosts'n Goblins]]''\n|[[Capcom]]\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|''[[Gradius (video game)|Gradius]]''\n|[[Konami]]\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|''[[Ice Climber]]''\n|Nintendo\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|''[[Ice Hockey (1988 video game)|Ice Hockey]]''\n|Nintendo\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|''[[The Legend of Zelda (video game)|The Legend of Zelda]]''\n|Nintendo\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|''[[Mario Bros.]]''\n|Nintendo\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|''[[Pro Wrestling (NES video game)|Pro Wrestling]]''\n|Nintendo\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|''[[River City Ransom]]''\n|Arc System Works\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|''[[Soccer (1985 video game)|Soccer]]''\n|Nintendo\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|''[[Super Mario Bros.]]''\n|Nintendo\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|''[[Super Mario Bros. 3]]''\n|Nintendo\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|''[[Tecmo Bowl]]''\n|[[Koei Tecmo]]\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|''[[Tennis (1984 video game)|Tennis]]''\n|Nintendo\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|''[[Yoshi (video game)|Yoshi]]''\n|Nintendo\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|-\n|